627\u0644\u0623\u0645\u0631|date=2020-03-03|website=\u0648\u0637\u0646|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mubasher.aljazeera.net/news/%D8%AA%D8%B3%D8%A7%D8%A1%D9%84%D9%88%D8%A7-%D8%B9%D9%86-%D8%AF%D9%88%D8%B1-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A5%D9%85%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D9%85%D8%BA%D8%B1%D8%AF%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%81%D8%A7%D8%B9%D9%84%D9%88%D9%86-%D9%85%D8%B9-%D8%AA%D9%87%D8%AF%D9%8A%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B3%D9%8A-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%82%D8%AA%D9%84|title=\u062a\u0633\u0627\u0621\u0644\u0648\u0627 \u0639\u0646 \u062f\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0627\u062a.. \u0645\u063a\u0631\u062f\u0648\u0646 \u064a\u062a\u0641\u0627\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0646 \u0645\u0639 \u062a\u0647\u062f\u064a\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633\u064a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0642\u062a\u0644|website=\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0632\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0645\u0628\u0627\u0634\u0631|language=ar|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n== Political Thought ==\nDr. Al-Nafisi talked about [[Bahraini uprising of 2011]], and he rejected it completely, describing it as an \"Iranian movement\", which sparked great controversy among Bahrain's Shiites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alayam.com/Article/Article/27204/Index.html#fbshare|title=\u062f.\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633\u064a..\u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0634\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062e\u064a\u0631 \u0641\u064a \u062f\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0637\u0634|website=www.alayam.com|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.akhbar-alkhaleej.com/news/article/1187422|title=\u062f. \u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633\u064a \u0648\u0635\u0646\u062f\u0648\u0642\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u0648\u062f|website=www.akhbar-alkhaleej.com|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAl-Nafisi also strongly supports the inclusion of [[Yemen]] in the [[Gulf Cooperation Council]] for its geographical location and its social and humanitarian proximity, to secure the Gulf and the [[Arabian Peninsula]] as a whole, and to pull Yemen out of complete chaos <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alaan.cc/article/54902/\u062e\u0644\u064a\u0644-\u0639\u0644\u064a-\u062d\u064a\u062f\u0631-\u064a\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0631-\u0623\u0637\u0631\u0648\u062d\u0629-\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633\u064a-\u0643\u0627\u0631\u062b\u064a\u0629-\u0648\u0645\u063a\u0627\u0645\u0631\u0629-\u0625\u0631\u0647\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0629-\u0628\u0634\u0639\u0629-\u0648\u0636\u0631\u0628\u0629-\u0644\u0623\u0646\u0638\u0645\u0629-\u0648\u062d\u0643\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a-\u062f\u0648\u0644-\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633-\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646/|title=\u062e\u0644\u064a\u0644 \u0639\u0644\u064a \u062d\u064a\u062f\u0631 \u064a\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0631 \u0623\u0637\u0631\u0648\u062d\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633\u064a '\u0643\u0627\u0631\u062b\u064a\u0629' \u0648\u0645\u063a\u0627\u0645\u0631\u0629 \u0625\u0631\u0647\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u0628\u0634\u0639\u0629 \u0648\u0636\u0631\u0628\u0629 \u0644\u0623\u0646\u0638\u0645\u0629 \u0648\u062d\u0643\u0648\u0645\u0627\u062a \u062f\u0648\u0644 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646|last=\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0644\u0643\u062a\u0631\u0648\u0646\u064a\u0629|first=\u062c\u0631\u064a\u062f\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0622\u0646|website=Alaan Online Newspaper|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAlso, in a tweet on his social networking site \"Twitter\", he said he recognized \"[[Ahvaz|Al-Ahwaz]] as an Arab country.\",  Al-Nafisi\u2019s tweet received great interaction within a short time of her publication, as she was retweeted from more than 1300 tweets within less than an hour of her post, in addition to the responses that were mostly supportive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://arabi21.com/story/852268/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633\u064a-\u0623\u0646\u0627-\u0623\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0641-\u0628\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062d\u0648\u0627\u0632-\u0643\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629-\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633\u064a: \u0623\u0646\u0627 \u0623\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0641 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062d\u0648\u0627\u0632 \u0643\u062f\u0648\u0644\u0629 \u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|date=2015-08-17|website=\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a21|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n\n* The role of Shiites in the modern political development of Iraq \u00a0 (PhD. thesis - Cambridge University 1972 - That Al Salasil - Kuwait). <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/21377971|title=\u062f\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0639\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u062a\u0637\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0642 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u0633\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u064a\u062b|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* Conflict in Dhofar (1975, Dar Al-Politics, Kuwait).<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u0622\u0645\u0646\u0629|first=\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0639\u060c|url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=4gELwI1xYLAC&pg=PT19&lpg=PT19&dq=%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B5%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%B9+%D9%81%D9%8A+%D8%B8%D9%81%D8%A7%D8%B1+%D8%B9%D8%A8%D8%AF%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87+%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%86%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B3%D9%8A&source=bl&ots=CarT__qdEA&sig=ACfU3U0C3uoM--IgqQy1Ej89-ghCrMi7Tw&hl=ar&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjVzcPz4tXoAhWJ2qQKHd7PBhcQ6AEwCHoECAwQLA|title=\u0627\u0644\u0628\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0631\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0642\u0635\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0635\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0633\u0644\u0637\u0646\u0629 \u0639\u0645\u0627\u0646 1980-2000|date=2005|publisher=AIRP|isbn=978-9953-36-693-7|language=ar}}</ref>\n* Kuwait, The Other Opinion (1978, Taha House - London).<ref>{{Citation|title=\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0623\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0622\u062e\u0631|date=2020-02-20|url=https://ar.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%B1%D8%A3%D9%8A_%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A2%D8%AE%D8%B1&oldid=43534033|work=\u0648\u064a\u0643\u064a\u0628\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627|language=ar|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/18927655|title=\u0627\u0644\u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a\u060c \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0623\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0627\u062e\u0631|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* Islam Rule (1980 Dar Taha - London).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/17378413|title=\u0639\u0646\u062f\u0645\u0627 \u064a\u062d\u0643\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neelwafurat.com/itempage.aspx?id=lbb218919-194424&search=books|title=Nwf.com: \u0639\u0646\u062f\u0645\u0627 \u064a\u062d\u0643\u0645 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645: \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0641\u064a\u0633: \u0643\u062a\u0628|website=www.neelwafurat.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* Sharia Policy (1980, Taha House - Kuwait).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/17329348|title=\u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0631\u0639\u064a\u0629|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* Gulf Cooperation Council: The Strategic Framework (1982 Dar Taha - London).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/18335938|title=\u0645\u062c\u0644\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0637\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u0633\u064a \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0633\u062a\u0631\u0627\u062a\u064a\u062c\u064a|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* The Islamic Movement: Gaps in the Road (1986 Dar Al-Rubaian - Kuwait).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/24172754|title=\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* The role of students in political work (1986, the National Union of Kuwaiti Students - Kuwait) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/15146704|title=\u062f\u0648\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0644\u0628\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u0627\u0633\u064a|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* Female work in Gulf : reality and aspirations (1987, Dar Al-Rubaian - Kuwait).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/18200618|title=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0645\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0633\u0627\u0626\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0627\u0642\u0639 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0631\u062a\u062c\u0649|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* Iran and the Gulf, Dialectics of Inclusion and Denunciation (2000, Qurtas House - Kuwait). <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/7694578|title=\u0625\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u062c|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* The World After the Battle of Manhattan, (2001) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/26169062|title=\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645 \u0628\u0639\u062f \u063a\u0632\u0648\u0629 \u0645\u0646\u0647\u0627\u062a\u0646|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n* Is Islam a threat to the West ? <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.neelwafurat.com/itempage.aspx?id=lbb123025-83154&search=books|title=Nwf.com: \u0647\u0644 \u064a\u0634\u0643\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u062e\u0637\u0631\u0627\u064b \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u063a\u0631\u0628\u061f: \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0641\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644: \u0643\u062a\u0628|website=www.neelwafurat.com|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> \n\nDr. Al-Nafisi has many articles in refereed scientific fields such as (International Politics) [[Al-Ahram]] - Cairo, (Journal of Social Sciences) Kuwait University, and (Journal of Gulf and Island Studies) Kuwait University.\n\n== Experience ==\n\n* Visiting professor at [[Peking University]], China 1973 \n* Visiting Professor at the [[Moscow State University|University of Moscow]] - the Soviet Union.1976 \n* Visiting Professor at [[Harvard University]] - Center for Middle Eastern Studies.1977 \n* Visiting Professor, [[Cambridge University]], Massachusetts, United States.1978 \n* Visiting Professor at [[Stanford University]] - Paulo Alto - USA.1978 \n* Visiting Professor at the University of Exeter - United Kingdom.1980 \n* Professor at the Department of Politics - [[United Arab Emirates University|Emirates University]] in Al Ain - United Arab Emirates.1981 - 1984 \n* He participated in the founding conference of the Arab Organization for Human Rights - Cyprus. He was a member of the organization's Board of Trustees for several years.1983 \n* Political advisor to the Speaker of the National Assembly, Ahmed Al-Saadoun - Kuwait.1992 - 1996\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Kuwaiti writers]]\n[[Category:Muslims]]\n[[Category:Sunni Muslims]]\n[[Category:American University of Beirut alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Churchill College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Kuwait University faculty]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti writers]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of Kuwait]]\n__INDEX__\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKuwaiti(link changed toDemographics of Kuwait) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdullah_Alnafisi"}
{"title_page": "Yasser Al-Habib", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| background = #ABE9CC\n| name = Yasser al-Habib \n|honorific-prefix= [[Sheikh]]\n| image = Yasser al habib.jpg\n| alt = \n| religion = [[Twelver Shia Islam]] ([[Ja'fari jurisprudence|Ja'fari]])\n| nationality = Stateless (formerly [[Demographics of Kuwait|Kuwaiti]])\n| ethnicity = Arab\n| founder   = [[Fadak (TV channel)]]\n|institute = [[Khoddam al-Mahdi]]\n| native_name={{lang|ar|\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u064a\u062d\u064a\u0649 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1979|1|20}}\n| birth_place = {{longitem|[[Kuwait]]}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| title = [[Sheikh]], [[Hujjat al-Islam]]\n| teacher = [[Mohammed Reza Shirazi|Ayatollah Mohammed Reza Shirazi]]\n| period = \n| successor = \n}}\n\n'''Yasser al-Habib''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628}} born 20 January 1979) is a Kuwaiti [[Twelver Shia]] [[Ulama|Muslim cleric]], and the head of the London-based Khoddam Al-Mahdi Organization, as well as Al-Muhassin mosque in [[Fulmer|Fulmer, Buckinghamshire]]. Al-Habib attempts to express his religious views and his investigations and conclusions in the Islamic history, based upon Shia and Sunni sources. \n\nAl-Habib started his religious activities in Kuwait, starting off as a member of the Dawah Party, later he founded a non-profit religious organization named Khoddam Al-Mahdi Organization, and he also expressed his religious views regarding [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]], and criticized them sharply, which led to anger the mainstream [[Sunnis]] in Kuwait and other Arabic-speaking Sunni communities, and finally led to the arrest of Al-Habib. Later, in February 2004 he was released under an annual pardon announced by the [[Emir of Kuwait]] on the occasion of the country's [[National Day#Kuwait|National Day]], but his rearrest was ordered a few days later. Al-Habib fled Kuwait before he was sentenced [[trial in absentia|''in absentia'']] to 10 years imprisonment,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/annualreport.php?id=ar&yr=2005&c=KWT |title=International Religious Freedom Report 2004 - Kuwait |publisher=Amnestyusa.org |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218151217/http://www.amnestyusa.org/annualreport.php?id=ar&yr=2005&c=KWT |archivedate=18 February 2011 }}</ref> and spent months in Iraq and Iran before gaining an asylum in [[United Kingdom]] which is his current place of residence.\n\n== Early life ==\nAl-Habib was interviewed by [[Elaph]], a well-known Arabic online newspaper, where he stated that he was born in a religious Kuwaiti family, and started his education in the Kuwaiti governmental schools, before joining [[Kuwait University]] and graduating from its Political sciences faculty. Besides his secular studies, Al-Habib stated that he studied the traditional Islamic sciences under the guidance of his teacher [[Mohammed Reza Shirazi|Ayatollah Mohammed Reza Shirazi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.elaph.com/Web/news/2010/11/614420.html |script-title=ar:\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628: \u0647\u0630\u0647 \u0642\u0635\u0629 \u062e\u0631\u0648\u062c\u064a \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062c\u0646.. \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0628\u0644 \u0644\u0644\u062a\u0634\u064a\u0639 |publisher=Elaph |date= |accessdate=2 February 2014|language=ar}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, he founded Khoddam Al-Mahdi Organization at [[Kuwait]] and In 2003, Al-Habib was sentenced to 10 years in prison in Kuwait for insulting Aisha and Sunni caliphs, who are revered in [[Sunni Islam]]. However, his imprisonment was cut short in 2004 on the occasion of the country's [[National Day#Kuwait|National Day]], but his rearrest was ordered a few days later. He fled the country first to Iraq, then to Iran. Then he went to London where Seyed [[Mojtaba Hosseini Shirazi]], younger brother of [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq Shirazi]], has lived for forty years. Finally he could get asylum in Britain.<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web | url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/meet-the-controversial-shia-cleric-bringing-sectarian-tension-to-the-uk | title=Meet the Controversial Cleric Threatening to Turn UK Muslims Against Each Other | date=10 May 2013 | accessdate=25 February 2015 | author=Omar Shahid and Tamanna Ali}}</ref>\n\nNow he lives in [[Fulmer |Fulmer, Buckinghamshire]], and had started his religious and political activity such as founding Al Muhassin Mosque and setting up [[Fadak (TV channel)]].<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/sunni-vs-shia-in-gerrards-cross-new-mosque-highlights-growing-tensions-among-british-muslims-8671969.html | title=Sunni vs Shia... in Gerrard's Cross: New mosque highlights growing tensions among British Muslims | publisher=The independent | date=24 June 2011 | author=Milmo Chahal}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nHe recorded two lectures in English titled: ''Who killed the Prophet Muhammad'' and ''Why do Shiites hate [[Umar]] Ibn al-Khattab''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/en/video-y/index.php?catb=5&part=1 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Video Youtube |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917085608/http://alqatrah.net/en/video-y/index.php?catb=5&part=1 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref>\nSunni Al-Sha'ab newspaper described Sheikh al-Habib as a traitor and [[apostate]] in its main page, at the time that Al-Habib cursed [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/edara/index.php?id=143 |title=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0637\u0631\u0629 - \u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0631\u0624\u0649 \u0648\u0645\u062d\u0627\u0636\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628 - \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0626\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u062a\u0641\u062a\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0631 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0643\u0627\u0630\u064a\u0628 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0641\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0621\u0627\u062a \u0641\u064a \u0648\u0633\u0627\u0626\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645 |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917072346/http://alqatrah.net/edara/index.php?id=143 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Quranism ===\n\nAl-Habib has criticized [[Quranism]] and claims that Quranists are followers of [[Umar bin Khattab]] <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ef8hjMR5llQ</ref>\n\n=== Wahhabism ===\nAl-Habib said: {{cquote|Wahhabism is a criminal and violent ideology, founded by a mentally ill man named Muhammad Ibn Abdul-Wahhab about three centuries ago. Its main principle is that all Muslims who perform [[Tawassul ]] and visit their graves are regarded as apostates and infidels. Therefore, the seizure of their life, property and women would, like that of the infidels, be religiously lawful and permissible!<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-drop.net/en/question/index.php?id=42 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Answers - What do Wahhabis believe in |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724094102/http://www.the-drop.net/en/question/index.php?id=42 |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref>}}\n\n=== Views on Sunnis ===\nSheikh al-Habib refers to Sunnis as [[Bakriyyah|Bakris]], meaning the followers of Abu Bakr. He says that the real Sunnis (''Ahlul Sunnah'') are the ones who follow the [[Sunnah]] of Muhammad, that is Shia Muslims. He continues that Sunnis today follow the Sunnah and teachings of Abu Bakr instead, having rejected [[Ali|Ali ibn Abi Talib]] and [[Ahlulbayt]]. He explains in one of his lectures titled ''Bakris think they are Sunnis, but in reality are not'' that when people wanted to distance themselves from the Shia, and follow [[Muawiyah I|Muawiyya]], they started calling themselves the Jama'ah. He explains that the reality behind why people called themselves [[Sunnis|Ahlul Sunnah wal Jama'ah]] only began after the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] ruler [[Umar bin Abdul Aziz]] forbade the Sunnah (tradition) of cursing [[Ali bin Abi Talib]] publicly (as previously invented by the [[Muawiyah I|Muawiyah]]). It was upon then that people protested to this new prohibition, declaring that [[Umar bin Abdul Aziz]] had prohibited the Sunnah of cursing [[Ali bin Abi Talib]]. Thus they began calling themselves Ahlul Sunnah wal Jama'ah; stressing that they adhere to the Sunnah of cursing [[Ali bin Abi Talib]], and that they are the Jama'ah of [[Muawiyah I|Muawiyah]].\n\nHe also refers to those people who claim that they belong to [[Shi'a]] but fail to disassociate themselves from [[Abu bakr]], [[Umar|Omar ibn khattab]], [[Aisha]] and other controversial historical personalities like [[Khalid ibn Walid]] as Batris.\n\nHe described [[Mohammad Hussein Fadlallah]] (the [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] [[Marja'|marja]] who died on 4 July 2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_id=1&categ_id=2&article_id=116761#ixzz0sr3wTEpL |title=Politics - Tuesday official mourning day for Fadlallah |publisher=The Daily Star |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref> as Batri. Al-Habib said that Fadlallah left a great number of doctrinal deviations, ignorant views and bad conduct which he introduced to the religion of [[Islam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=102 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Sheikh al-Habib Hails our Great Scholars\u2019 Refusal to pay tribute to Fadlullah |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917055848/http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=102 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Celebrating Aisha's death anniversary and its reaction ==\n\n[[File:CelebratingAisha'sDeath.jpg|thumb|left|Celebrating Aisha's death]]\n\n\nIn September 2010, Sheikh Yasser al-Habib angered the [[Sunni]] Muslims by calling [[Aisha]], \"an enemy of God\" which led Kuwait to revoke his citizenship accusing him of trying to stir up discord among Muslims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/cde302c6-c732-11df-aeb1-00144feab49a.html |title=Financial Times|publisher=ft.com |date= |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFLDE68M0QD20100923 |title=Reuters|publisher=reuters.com |date= |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wtopnews.com/?sid=2057568&nid=105 |title=Federal News Radio|publisher=wtop.com |date= |accessdate=20 September 2010}}</ref><ref>\n[http://www.newser.com/article/d9ibqf600/kuwait-strips-hard-line-shiite-activist-of-citizenship-after-claims-of-blasphemy.html Kuwait strips hard-line Shiite activist of citizenship after claims of blasphemy - 9-20-2010 12737 PM  Newser]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuwaitsamachar.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=51891:revoking-al-habibs-citizenship-premature-safar&catid=150:kuwait-times&Itemid=471|title=Revoking Al-Habib's citizenship premature Safar  KuwaitSamachar|website=www.kuwaitsamachar.com}}{{deadlink|date=June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iplextra.indiatimes.com/article/0cUh8ga7F7d9X?q=Kuwait |title=Kuwait strips Shiite activist of citizenship |accessdate=11 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713025737/http://iplextra.indiatimes.com/article/0cUh8ga7F7d9X?q=Kuwait |archivedate=13 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n\nIn October 2010, [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Iranian Supreme Leader]] [[Ali Khamenei]] tried to calm tensions between Shias and Sunnis by issuing a [[fatwa]] against insulting Muhammad's companions and wives.<ref name=\"Islam Times\"/> \n{{quote|Cursing the wives of the prophets and the wives of the Great Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is one of the taboos and prohibitions.<ref name=\"Islam Times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.islamtimes.org/en/doc/article/39715/fatwa-closes-the-doors-in-front-of-any-sedition-between-sunnis-and-shiites | title=Fatwa closes the doors in front of any sedition between the Sunnis and the Shiites | publisher=Islam Times | date=9 October 2010}}</ref>}}\n\n== Criticism ==\nAfter Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei issued the fatwa outlawing the insult of Sunni Dignitaries (Aisha, Abu Bakr and Umar ibn al-Khatt\u0101b),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tehrantimes.com/Index_view.asp?code=227879 |title=Tehran Times |publisher=tehrantimes.com |date= |accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref> Al-Habib responded by calling the Islamic Republic of Iran \"oppressive\". He continued by referring to [[Ali Khamenei|Khamenei]] as \"so-called Ali al-Khamenei \u2013 who pretends to be a Shia scholar\". His reasoning for naming the Iranian government as \"oppressive\" was because the \"regime in Iran today unjustly arrests anyone who celebrates the occasion of Farhat-ul-Zahra and prevents people from visiting the tomb of [[Pirouz Nahavandi|Abu Lulu]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.org/en/edara/index.php?id=123 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Sheikh al-Habib takes an oath to 'publicly' voice opposition to the enemies of Ahlul Bayt and warns al-Khamenei |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=24 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025093456/http://alqatrah.org/en/edara/index.php?id=123 |archivedate=25 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSenior Iranian cleric [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] has referred to Al-Habib as a \"hired agent or a mad man\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=122 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Sheikh al-Habib remarks on Naser Makarem Shirazi's statement |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=18 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025213853/http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=122 |archivedate=25 October 2010 }}</ref> and stated: \"Recently, an illiterate fool non clergy U.K citizen in the name of Shia has insulted sacred matters of Sunni Muslim brothers\".<ref name=\" ABNA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abna24.com/english/cultural/archive/2010/10/05/207567/story.html | title=Grand Shia Cleric Calls \"Yaser Alhabib\" a Fool | publisher=ABNA | date=5 October 2010 | author=Staff writer}}</ref>\n\nAl-Habib has been criticized by several figures and leaders who speak in the name of [[Shiism]] including [[Ammar Nakshawani]], leader of [[Hezbollah]] [[Hassan Nasrallah]], [[Ali Khamenei]] (who also issued a fatwa against cursing of Muhammad's companions) and [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]].\n\n== Response == \nSheikh maintains that all he does is teach Islam as it was and should be, something that was historically disordered by Sunnis and Iran since 1979, especially under the Khamenei.\n\n== Books by Al-Habib ==\n* {{Cite book|title=Obscenity: The Other Face of Aisha|publisher=Khodam Al Mahdi Organisation|year=2010|isbn=095662300X}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.the-drop.net/en/index.php The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Habib, Yasser Al}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Stateless people]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Critics of Sunni Islam]]\n[[Category:Critics of Wahhabism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| background = #ABE9CC\n| name = Yasser al-Habib \n|honorific-prefix= [[Sheikh]]\n| image = Yasser al habib.jpg\n| alt = \n| religion = [[Twelver Shia Islam]] ([[Ja'fari jurisprudence|Ja'fari]])\n| nationality = Stateless (formerly [[Kuwaiti]])\n| ethnicity = Arab\n| founder   = [[Fadak (TV channel)]]\n|institute = [[Khoddam al-Mahdi]]\n| native_name={{lang|ar|\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u064a\u062d\u064a\u0649 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1979|1|20}}\n| birth_place = {{longitem|[[Kuwait]]}}\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| title = [[Sheikh]], [[Hujjat al-Islam]]\n| teacher = [[Mohammed Reza Shirazi|Ayatollah Mohammed Reza Shirazi]]\n| period = \n| successor = \n}}\n\n'''Yasser al-Habib''' ({{lang-ar|\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628}} born 20 January 1979) is a Kuwaiti [[Twelver Shia]] [[Ulama|Muslim cleric]], and the head of the London-based Khoddam Al-Mahdi Organization, as well as Al-Muhassin mosque in [[Fulmer|Fulmer, Buckinghamshire]]. Al-Habib attempts to express his religious views and his investigations and conclusions in the Islamic history, based upon Shia and Sunni sources. \n\nAl-Habib started his religious activities in Kuwait, starting off as a member of the Dawah Party, later he founded a non-profit religious organization named Khoddam Al-Mahdi Organization, and he also expressed his religious views regarding [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]], and criticized them sharply, which led to anger the mainstream [[Sunnis]] in Kuwait and other Arabic-speaking Sunni communities, and finally led to the arrest of Al-Habib. Later, in February 2004 he was released under an annual pardon announced by the [[Emir of Kuwait]] on the occasion of the country's [[National Day#Kuwait|National Day]], but his rearrest was ordered a few days later. Al-Habib fled Kuwait before he was sentenced [[trial in absentia|''in absentia'']] to 10 years imprisonment,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amnestyusa.org/annualreport.php?id=ar&yr=2005&c=KWT |title=International Religious Freedom Report 2004 - Kuwait |publisher=Amnestyusa.org |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110218151217/http://www.amnestyusa.org/annualreport.php?id=ar&yr=2005&c=KWT |archivedate=18 February 2011 }}</ref> and spent months in Iraq and Iran before gaining an asylum in [[United Kingdom]] which is his current place of residence.\n\n== Early life ==\nAl-Habib was interviewed by [[Elaph]], a well-known Arabic online newspaper, where he stated that he was born in a religious Kuwaiti family, and started his education in the Kuwaiti governmental schools, before joining [[Kuwait University]] and graduating from its Political sciences faculty. Besides his secular studies, Al-Habib stated that he studied the traditional Islamic sciences under the guidance of his teacher [[Mohammed Reza Shirazi|Ayatollah Mohammed Reza Shirazi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://www.elaph.com/Web/news/2010/11/614420.html |script-title=ar:\u064a\u0627\u0633\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628: \u0647\u0630\u0647 \u0642\u0635\u0629 \u062e\u0631\u0648\u062c\u064a \u0645\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u062c\u0646.. \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0633\u062a\u0642\u0628\u0644 \u0644\u0644\u062a\u0634\u064a\u0639 |publisher=Elaph |date= |accessdate=2 February 2014|language=ar}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, he founded Khoddam Al-Mahdi Organization at [[Kuwait]] and In 2003, Al-Habib was sentenced to 10 years in prison in Kuwait for insulting Aisha and Sunni caliphs, who are revered in [[Sunni Islam]]. However, his imprisonment was cut short in 2004 on the occasion of the country's [[National Day#Kuwait|National Day]], but his rearrest was ordered a few days later. He fled the country first to Iraq, then to Iran. Then he went to London where Seyed [[Mojtaba Hosseini Shirazi]], younger brother of [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq Shirazi]], has lived for forty years. Finally he could get asylum in Britain.<ref name=\"vice\">{{cite web | url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/read/meet-the-controversial-shia-cleric-bringing-sectarian-tension-to-the-uk | title=Meet the Controversial Cleric Threatening to Turn UK Muslims Against Each Other | date=10 May 2013 | accessdate=25 February 2015 | author=Omar Shahid and Tamanna Ali}}</ref>\n\nNow he lives in [[Fulmer |Fulmer, Buckinghamshire]], and had started his religious and political activity such as founding Al Muhassin Mosque and setting up [[Fadak (TV channel)]].<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite web | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/sunni-vs-shia-in-gerrards-cross-new-mosque-highlights-growing-tensions-among-british-muslims-8671969.html | title=Sunni vs Shia... in Gerrard's Cross: New mosque highlights growing tensions among British Muslims | publisher=The independent | date=24 June 2011 | author=Milmo Chahal}}</ref>\n\n==Views==\nHe recorded two lectures in English titled: ''Who killed the Prophet Muhammad'' and ''Why do Shiites hate [[Umar]] Ibn al-Khattab''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/en/video-y/index.php?catb=5&part=1 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Video Youtube |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917085608/http://alqatrah.net/en/video-y/index.php?catb=5&part=1 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref>\nSunni Al-Sha'ab newspaper described Sheikh al-Habib as a traitor and [[apostate]] in its main page, at the time that Al-Habib cursed [[Abu Bakr]] and [[Umar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/edara/index.php?id=143 |title=\u0627\u0644\u0642\u0637\u0631\u0629 - \u0645\u0648\u0642\u0639 \u0631\u0624\u0649 \u0648\u0645\u062d\u0627\u0636\u0631\u0627\u062a \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628 - \u0627\u0644\u0637\u0627\u0626\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0629 \u062a\u0641\u062a\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0631 \u0639\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0628\u064a\u0628 \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0623\u0643\u0627\u0630\u064a\u0628 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0641\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0621\u0627\u062a \u0641\u064a \u0648\u0633\u0627\u0626\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645 |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917072346/http://alqatrah.net/edara/index.php?id=143 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n=== Quranism ===\n\nAl-Habib has criticized [[Quranism]] and claims that Quranists are followers of [[Umar bin Khattab]] <ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ef8hjMR5llQ</ref>\n\n=== Wahhabism ===\nAl-Habib said: {{cquote|Wahhabism is a criminal and violent ideology, founded by a mentally ill man named Muhammad Ibn Abdul-Wahhab about three centuries ago. Its main principle is that all Muslims who perform [[Tawassul ]] and visit their graves are regarded as apostates and infidels. Therefore, the seizure of their life, property and women would, like that of the infidels, be religiously lawful and permissible!<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-drop.net/en/question/index.php?id=42 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Answers - What do Wahhabis believe in |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724094102/http://www.the-drop.net/en/question/index.php?id=42 |archivedate=24 July 2011 }}</ref>}}\n\n=== Views on Sunnis ===\nSheikh al-Habib refers to Sunnis as [[Bakriyyah|Bakris]], meaning the followers of Abu Bakr. He says that the real Sunnis (''Ahlul Sunnah'') are the ones who follow the [[Sunnah]] of Muhammad, that is Shia Muslims. He continues that Sunnis today follow the Sunnah and teachings of Abu Bakr instead, having rejected [[Ali|Ali ibn Abi Talib]] and [[Ahlulbayt]]. He explains in one of his lectures titled ''Bakris think they are Sunnis, but in reality are not'' that when people wanted to distance themselves from the Shia, and follow [[Muawiyah I|Muawiyya]], they started calling themselves the Jama'ah. He explains that the reality behind why people called themselves [[Sunnis|Ahlul Sunnah wal Jama'ah]] only began after the [[Umayyad Caliphate|Umayyad]] ruler [[Umar bin Abdul Aziz]] forbade the Sunnah (tradition) of cursing [[Ali bin Abi Talib]] publicly (as previously invented by the [[Muawiyah I|Muawiyah]]). It was upon then that people protested to this new prohibition, declaring that [[Umar bin Abdul Aziz]] had prohibited the Sunnah of cursing [[Ali bin Abi Talib]]. Thus they began calling themselves Ahlul Sunnah wal Jama'ah; stressing that they adhere to the Sunnah of cursing [[Ali bin Abi Talib]], and that they are the Jama'ah of [[Muawiyah I|Muawiyah]].\n\nHe also refers to those people who claim that they belong to [[Shi'a]] but fail to disassociate themselves from [[Abu bakr]], [[Umar|Omar ibn khattab]], [[Aisha]] and other controversial historical personalities like [[Khalid ibn Walid]] as Batris.\n\nHe described [[Mohammad Hussein Fadlallah]] (the [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] [[Marja'|marja]] who died on 4 July 2010)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_id=1&categ_id=2&article_id=116761#ixzz0sr3wTEpL |title=Politics - Tuesday official mourning day for Fadlallah |publisher=The Daily Star |date=6 July 2010 |accessdate=27 September 2010}}</ref> as Batri. Al-Habib said that Fadlallah left a great number of doctrinal deviations, ignorant views and bad conduct which he introduced to the religion of [[Islam]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=102 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Sheikh al-Habib Hails our Great Scholars\u2019 Refusal to pay tribute to Fadlullah |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=27 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917055848/http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=102 |archivedate=17 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Celebrating Aisha's death anniversary and its reaction ==\n\n[[File:CelebratingAisha'sDeath.jpg|thumb|left|Celebrating Aisha's death]]\n\n\nIn September 2010, Sheikh Yasser al-Habib angered the [[Sunni]] Muslims by calling [[Aisha]], \"an enemy of God\" which led Kuwait to revoke his citizenship accusing him of trying to stir up discord among Muslims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/cde302c6-c732-11df-aeb1-00144feab49a.html |title=Financial Times|publisher=ft.com |date= |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://af.reuters.com/article/energyOilNews/idAFLDE68M0QD20100923 |title=Reuters|publisher=reuters.com |date= |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wtopnews.com/?sid=2057568&nid=105 |title=Federal News Radio|publisher=wtop.com |date= |accessdate=20 September 2010}}</ref><ref>\n[http://www.newser.com/article/d9ibqf600/kuwait-strips-hard-line-shiite-activist-of-citizenship-after-claims-of-blasphemy.html Kuwait strips hard-line Shiite activist of citizenship after claims of blasphemy - 9-20-2010 12737 PM  Newser]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kuwaitsamachar.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=51891:revoking-al-habibs-citizenship-premature-safar&catid=150:kuwait-times&Itemid=471|title=Revoking Al-Habib's citizenship premature Safar  KuwaitSamachar|website=www.kuwaitsamachar.com}}{{deadlink|date=June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://iplextra.indiatimes.com/article/0cUh8ga7F7d9X?q=Kuwait |title=Kuwait strips Shiite activist of citizenship |accessdate=11 September 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713025737/http://iplextra.indiatimes.com/article/0cUh8ga7F7d9X?q=Kuwait |archivedate=13 July 2011 }}</ref>\n\n\nIn October 2010, [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Iranian Supreme Leader]] [[Ali Khamenei]] tried to calm tensions between Shias and Sunnis by issuing a [[fatwa]] against insulting Muhammad's companions and wives.<ref name=\"Islam Times\"/> \n{{quote|Cursing the wives of the prophets and the wives of the Great Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is one of the taboos and prohibitions.<ref name=\"Islam Times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.islamtimes.org/en/doc/article/39715/fatwa-closes-the-doors-in-front-of-any-sedition-between-sunnis-and-shiites | title=Fatwa closes the doors in front of any sedition between the Sunnis and the Shiites | publisher=Islam Times | date=9 October 2010}}</ref>}}\n\n== Criticism ==\nAfter Iranian Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei issued the fatwa outlawing the insult of Sunni Dignitaries (Aisha, Abu Bakr and Umar ibn al-Khatt\u0101b),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tehrantimes.com/Index_view.asp?code=227879 |title=Tehran Times |publisher=tehrantimes.com |date= |accessdate=5 October 2010}}</ref> Al-Habib responded by calling the Islamic Republic of Iran \"oppressive\". He continued by referring to [[Ali Khamenei|Khamenei]] as \"so-called Ali al-Khamenei \u2013 who pretends to be a Shia scholar\". His reasoning for naming the Iranian government as \"oppressive\" was because the \"regime in Iran today unjustly arrests anyone who celebrates the occasion of Farhat-ul-Zahra and prevents people from visiting the tomb of [[Pirouz Nahavandi|Abu Lulu]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.org/en/edara/index.php?id=123 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Sheikh al-Habib takes an oath to 'publicly' voice opposition to the enemies of Ahlul Bayt and warns al-Khamenei |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=24 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025093456/http://alqatrah.org/en/edara/index.php?id=123 |archivedate=25 October 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSenior Iranian cleric [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]] has referred to Al-Habib as a \"hired agent or a mad man\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=122 |title=The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London - Sheikh al-Habib remarks on Naser Makarem Shirazi's statement |publisher=Alqatrah.net |accessdate=18 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025213853/http://alqatrah.net/en/edara/index.php?id=122 |archivedate=25 October 2010 }}</ref> and stated: \"Recently, an illiterate fool non clergy U.K citizen in the name of Shia has insulted sacred matters of Sunni Muslim brothers\".<ref name=\" ABNA\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abna24.com/english/cultural/archive/2010/10/05/207567/story.html | title=Grand Shia Cleric Calls \"Yaser Alhabib\" a Fool | publisher=ABNA | date=5 October 2010 | author=Staff writer}}</ref>\n\nAl-Habib has been criticized by several figures and leaders who speak in the name of [[Shiism]] including [[Ammar Nakshawani]], leader of [[Hezbollah]] [[Hassan Nasrallah]], [[Ali Khamenei]] (who also issued a fatwa against cursing of Muhammad's companions) and [[Naser Makarem Shirazi]].\n\n== Response == \nSheikh maintains that all he does is teach Islam as it was and should be, something that was historically disordered by Sunnis and Iran since 1979, especially under the Khamenei.\n\n== Books by Al-Habib ==\n* {{Cite book|title=Obscenity: The Other Face of Aisha|publisher=Khodam Al Mahdi Organisation|year=2010|isbn=095662300X}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.the-drop.net/en/index.php The drop, Office of Sheikh Al-Habib in London]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Habib, Yasser Al}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Kuwaiti religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Stateless people]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Critics of Sunni Islam]]\n[[Category:Critics of Wahhabism]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toKuwaiti(link changed toDemographics of Kuwait) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yasser_Al-Habib"}
{"title_page": "2018 Boston Red Sox season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox MLB yearly\n| name = Boston Red Sox\n| season = 2018\n| misc = [[2018 World Series|World Series]] Champions<br>[[2018 American League Championship Series|American League]] Champions <br> [[American League East]] Champions\n| image = Boston Red Sox cap logo.svg\n| current league = American League\n| y1 = 1901\n| division = [[American League East|East Division]]\n| y2 = 1969\n| Uniform logo =\n| ballpark = [[Fenway Park]]\n| y4 = 1912\n| city = [[Boston]]\n| y5 = 1901\n| record = 108\u201354 (.667)\n| divisional place = 1st\n| owners = [[John W. Henry]] ([[Fenway Sports Group]])\n| presbo = [[Dave Dombrowski]]\n| general managers = none (de facto by President of Baseball Operations)<!-- Dombrowski never had GM as an official title -->\n| managers = [[Alex Cora]]\n| television = [[New England Sports Network|NESN]]<br/>([[Dave O'Brien (sportscaster)|Dave O'Brien]], [[Jerry Remy]], [[Dennis Eckersley]], [[Steve Lyons (baseball)|Steve Lyons]], [[Tom Caron]])\n| radio = [[WEEI-FM]]<br/>[[Boston Red Sox Radio Network]]<br/>([[Joe Castiglione]], [[Tim Neverett]], [[Lou Merloni]])\n|next_season=2019 Boston Red Sox season\n}}\n\nThe '''2018 Boston Red Sox season''' was the 118th season in the team's history, and their 107th season at [[Fenway Park]]. Under first year manager [[Alex Cora]], the team finished with a 108\u201354 record, winning the [[American League East]] division title for the third consecutive season, and finished eight games ahead of the second-place [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]. The [[Boston Red Sox|Red Sox]] were the first [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] team to post 100 wins during the [[2018 Major League Baseball season|2018]] season, reaching that milestone for the first time since [[1946 Boston Red Sox season|1946]]; they were also the first team to clinch a berth in the [[2018 Major League Baseball season#Postseason|2018 postseason]].\n\nThe team set a new franchise record for wins in a season by surpassing the prior mark of 105 that had been set in [[1912 Boston Red Sox season|1912]]; they also won the most games by any MLB team since the [[2001 Seattle Mariners season|2001 Seattle Mariners]] won 116. [[Mookie Betts]] finished the season with the Major League [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|batting title]], hitting .346, while [[J. D. Martinez]] finished second in the majors with .330. Betts also won a [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]] and the [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award]]. Closer [[Craig Kimbrel]] became the fastest player in history to reach 300 career saves, finishing the season with 333.\n\nThe Red Sox entered the postseason as the top seed in the [[American League]], and defeated the Yankees in four games in the [[2018 American League Division Series|Division Series]]. They then defeated the defending champion [[2018 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]] in five games in the [[2018 American League Championship Series|Championship Series]], advancing to the [[2018 World Series|World Series]] where they defeated the [[2018 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]] in five games.\n\nIn early [[2020]], an MLB investigation was launched into the Red Sox electronically stealing pitching signs in violation of league rules during their 2018 season.<ref name=\"MLB hammers Astros, CBS Sports, Apr. 17, 2020\" />\n\n==Offseason==\n===October 2017===\n[[File:Fenway_Jim_Beam_Dugout_2018.jpg|thumb|right|Field-level premium seating near the first base area]]\n*On October 11, the Red Sox announced that [[John Farrell (manager)|John Farrell]] would not return as the team's manager for the 2018 season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Browne|first=Ian|title=Red Sox release manager John Farrell after five seasons|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/258211184/red-sox-dismiss-john-farrell/?topicId=27118122|website=[[MLB.com]]|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n*On October 22, the Red Sox announced that [[Alex Cora]], who spent 2005\u20132008 with the club, had signed a three-year deal to become the new manager of the team.<ref>{{cite web|last=Browne|first=Ian|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/259274274/red-sox-name-alex-cora-manager/|title=Sox finalize 3-year deal with Cora to manage|website=[[MLB.com]]|date=October 22, 2017|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n*On October 25, it was reported that the Red Sox received approval from the Boston Landmarks Commission to add premium seating next to both dugouts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/redsox/2017/10/25/fenway-park-exploring-concept-dugout-style-seating/aNsnaV2MhWKx68bPKueA3N/story.html |title=Fenway Park may offer fans their own dugout seats |first=Nicole |last=Yang |newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=October 25, 2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> The seats, later branded the [[Jim Beam]] Dugout, became available for the 2018 season, at per-game prices starting at $12,500 for 25 guests.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/bos/suites/premium-suites/jim-beam-dugout/ |title=JIM BEAM DUGOUT |website=[[MLB.com]] |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*On October 26, the [[Cleveland Indians]] hired [[pitching coach]] [[Carl Willis]] and the [[Chicago Cubs]] hired [[hitting coach]] [[Chili Davis]] and third base coach [[Brian Butterfield]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mastrodonato|first=Jason|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/red_sox/clubhouse_insider/2017/10/red_sox_coaches_carl_willis_chili_davis_brian_butterfield|title=Red Sox coaches Carl Willis, Chili Davis, Brian Butterfield move on|website=[[bostonherald.com]]|date=October 26, 2017|accessdate=October 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===November 2017===\n* On November 2, the Red Sox named [[Carlos Febles]] as their [[third base coach]]; Febles has been in the Red Sox organization since 2007, and most recently was manager of the [[Portland Sea Dogs]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2017/11/02/red-sox-promote-sea-dogs-manager-to-become-third-base-coach/ |title=Red Sox promote Sea Dogs manager to become third-base coach |first=Kevin |last=Thomas |newspaper=[[Portland Press Herald]] |location=[[Portland, Maine]] |date=November 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> The same day, the Red Sox named [[Ron Roenicke]] as [[bench coach]]; he previously managed the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] (2011\u20132015) and most recently was third base coach of the [[Los Angeles Angels]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/red_sox/clubhouse_insider/2017/11/red_sox_hire_ex_brewers_manager_ron_roenicke_as_bench_coach |title=Red Sox hire ex-Brewers manager Ron Roenicke as bench coach |first=Jason |last=Mastrodonato |newspaper=[[Boston Herald]] |date=November 2, 2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* On November 4, [[Tim Hyers]] was named [[hitting coach]] of the Red Sox; he was previously with the team from 2013 through 2015 as minor league hitting coordinator, then spent 2016 and 2017 as assistant hitting coach for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.redsox.mlb.com/news/article/260692438/red-sox-choose-tim-hyers-as-hitting-coach/ |title=Red Sox choose Tim Hyers as hitting coach |last=Browne |first=Ian |date=November 4, 2017 |website=[[MLB.com]] |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* On November 8, the Red Sox named [[Dana LeVangie]] as their [[pitching coach]]; LeVangie has been with the Red Sox since 1991; he was a minor league player (1991\u20131996), bullpen catcher (1997\u20132004), and a scout (2005\u20132012) before joining the coaching staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/red-sox-hire-3-to-join-mlb-coaching-staff/c-261020296 |title=Red Sox announce trio of coaching hires |first=Ian |last=Browne |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=November 8, 2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n* On November 13, the Red Sox hired [[Craig Bjornson]] as their [[bullpen coach]]; Bjornson had been in the same role with the [[Houston Astros]] for the 2014 though 2017 seasons.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/craig-bjornson-new-red-sox-bullpen-coach/c-261732850 |title=Red Sox hire Bjornson to be bullpen coach |first=Ian |last=Browne |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=November 13, 2017 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===December 2017===\n[[File:Fenway_Safety_Netting_2018.jpg|thumb|right|Safety netting near the third base line]]\n*On December 18, the Red Sox re-signed first baseman [[Mitch Moreland]] to a two-year, $13M contract.<ref>{{cite web|last=Browne|first=Ian|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/red-sox-sign-mitch-moreland-for-two-years/c-263726344|title=Rod Sox re-sign Moreland, J.D. Still In Play|website=[[MLB.com]]|date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===January 2018===\n* On January 22, it was reported that the safety netting at Fenway Park would be extended down both foul lines; to Section 79 in left field and to Section 9 in right field.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/01/red-sox-netting-mlb-stadium-fenway-park-yankee-stadium-protective-fan-hurt-foul-ball-rules |title=The Red Sox are dramatically expanding netting at Fenway after scary incidents |first=Andrew |last=Joseph |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=January 22, 2018 |accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===February 2018===\n*On February 5\u2014\"Truck Day\"\u2014equipment for [[spring training]] left [[Fenway Park]] for [[jetBlue Park at Fenway South]].<ref name=SpringTraining>{{cite news |url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2017/11/20/red-sox-2018-spring-training-report-dates-mlb/ |title=Red Sox Announce Report Dates For 2018 Spring Training |website=[[WBZ-TV]] |date=November 20, 2017 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*On February 14, pitchers and catchers had their first workout at spring training.<ref name=SpringTraining/>\n*On February 18, the Red Sox re-signed IF [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] to a one-year, $4M deal.<ref>{{cite web|last=Todd|first=Jeff|url=https://www.mlbtraderumors.com/2018/02/momentum-toward-reunion-between-red-sox-eduardo-nunez.html|title=Red Sox Re-Sign Eduardo Nunez|work=MLB Trade Rumors|date=February 18, 2018|accessdate=February 20, 2018}}</ref>\n*On February 19, the team had its first full squad workout at spring training.<ref name=SpringTraining/>\n*On February 22, the team played exhibition games against the [[Northeastern Huskies baseball|Northeastern Huskies]] and the [[Boston College Eagles baseball|Boston College Eagles]];<ref name=SpringTraining/> the Red Sox won both games, by scores of 15\u20132 and 4\u20132, respectively.<ref name=FebResults>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/redsox/schedule/2018-02 |title=Boston Red Sox Schedule |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=February 2018 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n*On February 23, the team played its first [[Grapefruit League]] game, against the [[2018 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]];<ref name=SpringTraining/> the Red Sox won, 4\u20133.<ref name=FebResults/>\n*On February 26, the Red Sox announced they signed OF/DH [[J. D. Martinez]] to a five-year, $110M deal.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cole|first=Mike|url=https://nesn.com/2018/02/its-finally-official-red-sox-announce-j-d-martinezs-five-year-contract/|title=It's (Finally) Official: Red Sox Announce J.D. Martinez's Five-Year Contract|work=NESN.com|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n* On February 28, the Red Sox announced that they had filed a petition with the City of Boston to change the name of [[Yawkey Way]]\u2014the street where the main entrance of Fenway Park is located\u2014to its original name, Jersey Street.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/02/28/red-sox-petition-change-name-yawkey-way |title=Red Sox file petition to officially change name of Yawkey Way |first=Nicole |last=Yang |website=[https://boston.com] |date=February 28, 2018 |accessdate=February 28, 2018}}</ref> The change was approved in April 2018, and the name reverted in May 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/news/local-news/2018/05/03/yawkey-way-signs-come-down-outside-fenway-park |title=Yawkey Way signs come down outside Fenway Park |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=May 3, 2018 |accessdate=May 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===March 2018===\n*On March 24, the Red Sox traded IF [[Deven Marrero]] to the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] for a [[player to be named later]] or cash considerations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Randall|first=Dakota|url=https://nesn.com/2018/03/red-sox-trade-deven-marrero-to-d-backs-for-player-to-be-named-later-or-cash/|title=Red Sox Trade Deven Marrero To D-Backs For Player To Be Named Later Or Cash|work=NESN.com|date=March 24, 2018|accessdate=March 27, 2018}}</ref>\n*On March 27, the team played its final spring training game, defeating the [[2018 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]], 4\u20132.<ref name=MarchResults>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/redsox/schedule/2018-03 |title=Boston Red Sox Schedule |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 2018 |accessdate=May 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Regular season==\n===Opening Day, March 29 at [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]===\nThe 2018 regular season began on March 29, 2018, against the [[Tampa Bay Rays]] at [[Tropicana Field]]. Manager [[Alex Cora]] named [[Chris Sale]] as the Red Sox opening day starter opposite [[Chris Archer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/red-sox-name-chris-sale-opening-day-starter/c-269226860|title=Red Sox name Chris Sale Opening Day starter|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/chris-sale-chris-archer-to-duel-on-opening-day/c-269894428|title=Chris Sale Chris Archer to duel on Opening Day|website=MLB.com|language=en|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> The Red Sox built a 4\u20130 lead through seven innings, including an [[inside-the-park home run]] by [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]. Sale pitched six innings, giving up just one hit and walking three, while striking out nine. After [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] held the Rays scoreless in the seventh inning, [[Joe Kelly (pitcher)|Joe Kelly]] and [[Carson Smith (baseball)|Carson Smith]] gave up a total of six runs in the eighth inning, allowing Tampa Bay to take a 6\u20134 lead. Rays closer [[\u00c1lex Colom\u00e9]] pitched a scoreless ninth inning for the [[Save (baseball)|save]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/boxscore?gameId=380329130 |title=Red Sox vs. Rays - Box Score - March 29, 2018 |website=[[ESPN]] |date=March 29, 2018 |accessdate=March 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Opening Day lineup====\n[[File:Chris Sale in 2017 (37185846582) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Opening Day starter Chris Sale]]\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|50 || [[Mookie Betts]] || RF\n|-\n|16 || [[Andrew Benintendi]] || LF\n|-\n|13 || [[Hanley Ram\u00edrez]] || 1B\n|-\n|28 || [[J. D. Martinez]] || DH\n|-\n|&nbsp;2 || [[Xander Bogaerts]] || SS\n|-\n|11 || [[Rafael Devers]] || 3B\n|-\n|36 || [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] || 2B\n|-\n|19 || [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] || CF\n|-\n|&nbsp;7 || [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] || C\n|-\n|41 || [[Chris Sale]] || P\n|}\n\n{{collapse top|title=March/April}}\n\n===March===\n'''March 29\u2013March 31, at [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br />\nAfter the tough loss on opening day, [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] made his 2018 debut and threw seven shut-out innings on just 76 pitches. [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] and [[Craig Kimbrel]] shut the door. The lone run of the game was scored by [[Xander Bogaerts]] in the seventh. In game three of the four-game series, the baseball was handed to [[Rick Porcello]], who pitched {{frac|5|1|3}} innings and allowed one run on six hits. Bogaerts went 3-for-4, scored a run, drove in two, and hit his fifth double of the season.\n\n===April===\n'''April 1, at [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]] (cont.)'''<br />\nFor the third game in a row, the Red Sox won the match by the smallest of margins. [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]] allowed one run in {{frac|5|2|3}} innings. [[Mookie Betts]] and [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] scored to win the series.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (10\u20139 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 2\u2013April 3, at [[2018 Miami Marlins season|Miami Marlins]]'''<br />\nIn the series opener, [[Brian Johnson (pitcher)|Brian Johnson]] made his season debut and continued the strong start of Boston's starting pitching. He allowed only one run in six innings, while [[Hanley Ram\u00edrez]] and [[Mookie Betts]] went yard for the first time of the young season. Final score, 7\u20133 for Boston. The next day, [[Chris Sale]] exited the game after five innings with the score tied 1\u20131, followed by five scoreless frames. The Red Sox scored in the top of the 11th, but the Marlins got a tying run off of [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] in the bottom of the 11th. Ram\u00edrez then drove in Betts and [[Andrew Benintendi]] in the top of the 13th, with [[Heath Hembree]] picking up the win, 4\u20132.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20130 (11\u20135 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 5\u2013April 8, vs. [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] pitched seven innings, giving up no runs on three hits, but the Red Sox had to force extra innings with two runs in the bottom of the ninth. After two scoreless extra frames, [[Hanley Ram\u00edrez]] hit a bases-loaded single in the bottom of the 12th to give Boston the win, 3\u20132. After a rare scheduled Friday off-day, Boston jumped out to an 8\u20132 lead after two innings of the series' second game, en route to a 10\u20133 victory. In the series' finale on Sunday, Tampa Bay held a 7\u20132 lead with two outs in the bottom of the eighth; Boston then had six consecutive hits (three singles and three doubles) to take the lead, 8\u20137. [[Craig Kimbrel]] pitched a one-two-three ninth, to give the Red Sox the sweep.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (21\u201312 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 10\u2013April 12, vs. [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br />\nThe Red Sox jumped out to an early lead, then added a nine-run sixth inning, to take the first game of the series, 14\u20131. The first third of the Boston batting order was a combined 8-for-10 with eight runs and nine RBIs. Boston's winning streak then ended at nine games in a 10\u20137 loss to [[Masahiro Tanaka]] on April 11. The game included an incident where Red Sox relief pitcher [[Joe Kelly (pitcher)|Joe Kelly]] hit Yankees' [[designated hitter]] [[Tyler Austin]] with a pitch, following an allegedly dirty slide by Austin in which he spiked fielder [[Brock Holt]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thecomeback.com/mlb/benches-clear-at-fenway-park-after-hard-slide-from-yankees-tyler-austin.html|title=Benches repeatedly clear at Fenway Park after hard slide from Yankees' Tyler Austin|date=2018-04-11|work=The Comeback|access-date=2018-04-24|language=en-US}}</ref> Austin charged Kelly and started a bench-clearing brawl; four players, including Kelly and Austin, were ejected.<ref>{{cite web|title=Benches clear twice, 4 ejected as Yankees top Red Sox 10-7|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/benches-empty-between-red-sox-and-yankees/c-271768568|website=MLB|accessdate=April 12, 2018}}</ref> Boston subsequently won the final game of the series, 6\u20133, with [[Rick Porcello]] allowing only two hits in seven shutout innings.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (27\u201314 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Craig Kimbrel (33847580110).jpg|thumb|right|Craig Kimbrel had seven saves through the end of April.]]\n'''April 13\u2013April 15, vs. [[2018 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br />\nThe Red Sox jumped out to a 4\u20131 lead in the first inning of the opening game of the series. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] held the Orioles to one run in six innings, en route to a 7\u20133 win. Boston again took an early lead in the second game; 3\u20130 at the end of the first, and 8\u20130 at the end of the fourth. [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]] got the win in the 10\u20133 victory. The third game of the series was tied 1\u20131 through five innings, with Boston getting the go-ahead run in the sixth on an error and [[wild pitch]], and then an insurance run on a [[Tzu-Wei Lin]] [[ground rule double]]. [[Heath Hembree]] got the win in relief; final score 3\u20131. The final game of the series\u2014set for [[Patriots' Day]]\u2014was rained out and rescheduled for May 17.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (20\u20137 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 17\u2013April 19, at [[2018 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, the Red Sox got three early runs off of [[Shohei Ohtani]], who only lasted two innings. Boston added five more in the third, en route to a 10\u20131 win; [[Mookie Betts]] had three home runs. Boston again jumped out to an early lead in the second game; up 6\u20130 after three, starter [[Rick Porcello]] and the bullpen held Los Angeles scoreless, for a 9\u20130 victory. The final game of the series found Boston up a run, 3\u20132, at the end of five. The Red Sox then outscored the Angels 5\u20130 during the final four innings, for an 8\u20132 win to complete the sweep.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (27\u20133 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 20\u2013April 22, at [[2018 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]]'''<br />\nAfter a come-from-behind victory in the first game of the series, which extended Boston's winning streak to eight games, the Red Sox were [[no-hitter|no-hit]] by [[Sean Manaea]] on April 21.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/boxscore?gameId=380421111 |title=Red Sox vs. Athletics - Box Score |website=[[ESPN]] |date=April 21, 2018 |accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> Entering the game with a 17\u20132 record, the Red Sox had the best winning percentage (.895) of any MLB team ever no-hit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/cut4/sean-manaea-no-hits-red-hot-red-sox/c-273315966|title=The Red Sox were red-hot, but it didn't stop Sean Manaea from twirling a no-hitter|last=Mearns|first=Andrew|date=April 22, 2018|website=MLB.com Cut4}}</ref> It was the first no-hitter against the Red Sox since [[Chris Bosio]] of the [[Seattle Mariners]] on April 22, 1993.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/recap?gameId=380421111 |title=A's lefty Sean Manaea pitches first no-hitter vs. Red Sox in 25 years |website=[[ESPN]] |date=April 22, 2018 |accessdate=April 22, 2018}}</ref> Boston also lost the third and final game of the series; it was the first time the team had consecutive losses during the season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (8\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 24\u2013April 26, at [[2018 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, the Red Sox rallied from a 3\u20131 deficit in the top of the ninth, and the game went to extra innings. In the bottom of the 10th inning, [[Curtis Granderson]] hit a one-out solo home run off of [[Craig Kimbrel]] to give the Blue Jays a 4\u20133 win, extending Boston's losing streak to three games. The Red Sox were able to win the final two games of the series, each by a single run with Kimbrel getting both saves, giving them six wins from their nine-game road trip.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (12\u201311 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 27\u2013April 29, vs. [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br />\nAfter falling behind 4\u20130 in the first game of the series, the Red Sox rallied but came up a run short, losing 4\u20133 to the Rays. In the second game of the series, after playing to a 5\u20135 tie through five innings, the Red Sox gave up seven runs in the final four innings, losing 12\u20136, their fifth loss in seven games. Boston then won the final game of the series, 4\u20133.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (13\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''April 30, vs. [[2018 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]]'''<br />\nAfter giving up three first-inning runs, the Red Sox rallied to a 10\u20136 win in the opening game of the series. Four runs came on a [[Xander Bogaerts]] [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]], making the 2018 Red Sox only the second team in MLB history, along with the [[1996 Montreal Expos season|1996 Montreal Expos]], to have six grand slams by May 1.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/xander-bogaerts-hits-red-soxs-6th-grand-slam/c-274523748 |title=In 21st win, Sox's 6th slam ties '96 Expos mark |first=Ian |last=Browne |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=April 30, 2018 |accessdate=April 30, 2018}}</ref> The 19 wins the Red Sox had in April set a new club record; the prior mark was 18, most recently accomplished by the [[2013 Boston Red Sox season|2013 team]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/04/30/what-a-month-red-sox-complete-best-april-with-win-over-kc |title=What a month: Red Sox complete best April with win over Kansas City |first=Ken |last=Powtak |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=April 30, 2018 |accessdate=May 1, 2018}}</ref>\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=May}}\n\n===May===\n[[File:Fenway Scoreboard 02-May-2018.jpg|thumb|right|Scoreboard at the conclusion of the May 2 game]]\n'''May 1\u2013May 2, vs. [[2018 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]] (cont.)'''<br />\nA [[Save opportunity|blown save]] by [[Craig Kimbrel]], in giving up a ninth-inning home run to [[Alex Gordon]], sent the second game of the series into extra innings. With the Red Sox down a run in the bottom of the 12th, a home run by [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] tied the game, 4\u20134. A three-run home run by [[Jorge Soler]] in the top of the 13th put the Royals up 7\u20134, and a Red Sox rally in the bottom of the inning came up a run short, the Royals winning 7\u20136. The Royals took an early 3\u20130 lead in the rubber match of the series but the Red Sox tied the game in the fourth with [[Mookie Betts]] and [[J. D. Martinez]] going yard. Betts then single-handedly won the game for Boston, by taking [[Danny Duffy]] deep two more times. This was Betts' fourth three-homer game of his young career, making him the Red Sox' franchise leader for such games, surpassing [[Ted Williams]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/05/02/mookie-betts-homers-red-sox-royals |title=Mookie Betts homers 3 times as Red Sox beat Royals 5-4 |first=Ken |last=Powtak |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=May 2, 2018 |accessdate=May 2, 2018}}</ref><br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (21\u201317 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 3\u2013May 6, at [[2018 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]]'''<br />\nIn the series opener, [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] lasted only {{frac|3|2|3}} innings while giving up nine runs (seven earned) as the Red Sox lost to the Rangers, 11\u20135. [[Mookie Betts]] followed up his three-homer game with a 2-for-4 effort at the plate, including his 12th home run of the season. In the second game of the series, [[Rick Porcello]] held the Rangers to three hits and one run in six innings, as the Red Sox won, 5\u20131. The Red Sox had four home runs; Betts (his fifth in three games), [[J. D. Martinez]], and two by [[Rafael Devers]]. After falling behind 4\u20131 in the third game of the series, the Red Sox came back to win, 6\u20135, with [[Craig Kimbrel]] getting the [[Save (baseball)|save]], the 300th of his MLB career.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/05/05/craig-kimbrel-youngest-pitcher-saves |title=Craig Kimbrel becomes youngest pitcher reach 300 saves in Boston's 6-5 win over Texas |first=Stephen |last=Hawkins |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=May 5, 2018 |accessdate=May 5, 2018}}</ref> In the fourth and final game of the series, [[Chris Sale]] held the Rangers to four hits and one run in seven innings of work, en route to a 6\u20131 Red Sox victory.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (22\u201318 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 8\u2013May 10, at [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br />\nIn the opening game of the series, Boston outhit New York, 8\u20136, but the Yankees had two solo home runs from [[Giancarlo Stanton]] en route to a 3\u20132 win. It was the Yankees' ninth win in their last ten games, putting them into a tie with the Red Sox atop the [[American League East|AL East]], with identical 25\u201310 records. In the second game of the series, after trailing 4\u20132 at the end of the third, the Red Sox held a 6\u20135 lead going into the bottom of the eighth. With runners on first and second with one out, [[Craig Kimbrel]] was brought in, for a potential five-out save. A triple by [[Brett Gardner]], followed by an [[Aaron Judge]] two-run homer, put the Yankees ahead, 9\u20136. [[Aroldis Chapman]] pitched a scoreless ninth to give the Yankees the win, and first place in the AL East standings. In the final game of the series, the Red Sox held a 4\u20130 lead going into the bottom of the seventh, with [[Hanley Ram\u00edrez]] having contributed three RBIs. The Yankees loaded the bases with one out off of [[Heath Hembree]], and were able to push across four runs to tie the game after [[Joe Kelly (pitcher)|Joe Kelly]] came in. The Red Sox re-took the lead in the top of the eighth, on a [[J. D. Martinez]] solo home run. Kelly then held the Yankees scoreless in the bottom of the eighth, and Craig Kimbrel pitched a one-two-three ninth, earning his tenth save of the season. The win put the Red Sox back into a tie with the Yankees for first place in the AL East, both teams at 26\u201311.<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (13\u201316 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 11\u2013May 13, at [[2018 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, [[Chris Sale]] became the third Boston pitcher, after [[Roger Clemens]] and [[Pedro Mart\u00ednez]], to have a game with 15 strikeouts while issuing no walks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/recap?gameId=380511114 |title=Maile hits game-winning HR in 12th, Jays beat Red Sox 5-3 |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[ESPN]] |date=May 11, 2018 |accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref> Sale pitched nine innings of a game that would go 12 innings, with Toronto winning 5\u20133 on a two-run [[walk-off home run]] by [[Luke Maile]] off of [[Brian Johnson (pitcher)|Brian Johnson]]. In the second game of the series, [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] pitched {{frac|5|1|3}} innings, giving up two runs and getting the win, after his scheduled start against the Yankees had been pushed back due to numbness in his throwing hand, which was subsequently diagnosed as a mild case of [[carpal tunnel syndrome]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/23453106/boston-red-sox-david-price-carpal-tunnel-syndrome |title=Red Sox pitcher David Price dealing with carpal tunnel syndrome |website=[[ESPN]] |date=May 10, 2018 |accessdate=May 12, 2018}}</ref> [[Hanley Ram\u00edrez]] had a two-run homer en route to a 5\u20132 Boston win. In the final game of the series, a first-inning two-run home run from [[J. D. Martinez]] put Boston ahead early. After starter [[Drew Pomeranz]] left with no outs in the fifth inning, the Red Sox bullpen allowed one inherited runner to score, and then held Toronto to no further runs through the end of the game. [[Joe Kelly (pitcher)|Joe Kelly]] picking up his second save of the season, in a Boston 5\u20133 victory.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (13\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 14\u2013May 16, vs. [[2018 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]]'''<br />\nThe opening game of the series included five solo home runs; three by Oakland and two by Boston. The Red Sox trailed from the fourth inning on, ultimately losing 6\u20135. Rain delayed the start of the second game of the series by almost two hours. Oakland jumped out to a 2\u20130 lead in the first inning, and Boston closed the gap to 3\u20132 after five innings. The Athletics added two runs in the eighth, and although the Red Sox got one run in the ninth, closer [[Blake Treinen]] converted his second save in two days as the Athletics won, 5\u20133. In the third game of the series, [[Chris Sale]] handed over a 3\u20132 lead to the bullpen after five innings, due to a high [[pitch count]] (102). Boston again outscored Oakland 3\u20132 in the final four innings, for a 6\u20134 final.<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (14\u201315 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Mookie Betts hitting the ball (36478781664).jpg|thumb|right|Mookie Betts hit his 15th home run of the season against Baltimore on May 19.]]\n'''May 17\u2013May 20, vs. [[2018 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br />\n[[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] threw a 95-pitch complete game in the first game of the series, as the Red Sox won, 6\u20132. Baltimore's only runs came on a [[Manny Machado]] two-run homer with two outs in the ninth. With the win, the Red Sox became the first MLB team to reach 30 wins in the 2018 season. The second game of the series was tied at one in the top of the fourth with two outs, when Baltimore scored four runs off of Boston starter [[Drew Pomeranz]]. Despite a 3-for-5 effort from [[Mookie Betts]], including his 14th home run of the season, the Red Sox could not make up the deficit; final score 7\u20134 for the Orioles. In the third game of the series, the Red Sox broke a 1\u20131 tie with three runs in the fifth inning, on back-to-back home runs from Betts (with [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] on base) and [[Andrew Benintendi]]. [[Craig Kimbrel]] earned his 13th save of the season in closing out the 6\u20133 victory. In the final game of the series, a pair of [[J. D. Martinez]] home runs helped lead Boston to a 5\u20130 win; the Orioles outhit the Red Sox, 13\u201312, but were unable to score as they had 14 men [[left on base]].<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (21\u201312 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 22\u2013May 24, at [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, [[Chris Sale]] pitched {{frac|7|2|3}} innings while holding the Rays to two runs (one earned) while striking out nine and walking two. [[Mookie Betts]] and [[Rafael Devers]] both homered as the Red Sox won, 4\u20132. The second game of the series was tied 1\u20131 entering the ninth, when Boston pushed across three runs, aided by an error, walk, and [[passed ball]] by Tampa Bay. Closer [[Craig Kimbrel]] then retired the Rays in order for his 15th save of the season. Tampa Bay took the final game of the series, 6\u20133, as [[Rick Porcello]] gave up six runs (four earned) in {{frac|3|2|3}} innings, requiring 92 [[pitch count|pitches]].<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (11\u20139 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 25\u2013May 27, vs. [[2018 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]]'''<br />\nThe series' first game was a 6\u20132 win for the Red Sox, powered by home runs from [[J. D. Martinez]], [[Xander Bogaerts]], [[Mookie Betts]], and [[Mitch Moreland]]. [[Dustin Pedroia]] was on the active roster for the first time of the season, but did not play in the game. Earlier in the day, in order to open up a roster spot for Pedroia, the team announced that [[Hanley Ram\u00edrez]] had been [[designated for assignment]]. In the second game of the series, neither starting pitcher lasted four innings, and the two teams used a total of nine relief pitchers. [[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]] was the most effective, pitching three innings of scoreless relief and picking up the win, as the Red Sox rallied from deficits of 3\u20130 and 5\u20133 to win, 8\u20136. [[Chris Sale]] had eight strikeouts in {{frac|4|1|3}} innings of the final game of the series, but was roughed up for six runs by Atlanta, as Boston lost 7\u20131.<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (15\u201315 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Fenway Park - Memorial Day 2018 pregame ceremony.jpg|thumb|right|[[Memorial Day]] pregame ceremony on May 28]]\n'''May 28\u2013May 30, vs. [[2018 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, the Red Sox sent eight men to the plate in the bottom of the fourth, pushing across five runs on the way to an 8\u20133 victory. [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] gave up four hits and two runs over five innings, picking up the win as the bullpen allowed just one run through the final four innings. [[Andrew Benintendi]] had a 3-for-5 day with four RBIs, missing just a double to [[hitting for the cycle|complete the cycle]]. The second game of the series also yielded an 8\u20133 Boston win, as the Red Sox scored in six of the eight innings they batted, including home runs from Benintendi and [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]]. [[Rick Porcello]] improved his record to 7\u20132, and [[Craig Kimbrel]] notched his 17th save. Boston completed the sweep with a 6\u20134 win in the final game of the series. Toronto tied the game at two in the top of the sixth, and later rallied for two runs in the top of the ninth, before coming up short. [[J. D. Martinez]] hit his 18th home run of the 2018 season, putting him into a tie with [[Mike Trout]] of the [[2018 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]] for the MLB lead in that category.<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (22\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''May 31, at [[2018 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]]'''<br />\nThe Astros scored two first-innings runs on a [[Carlos Correa]] home run off of [[Drew Pomeranz]] en route to a 4\u20132 win in the first game of the series.\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=June}}\n\n===June===\n[[File:Rick Porcello on April 24, 2015.jpg|thumb|right|[[Rick Porcello]]'s win on June 3 pushed his record to 8\u20132.]]\n'''June 1\u2013June 3, at [[2018 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]] (cont.)'''<br />\nIn the second game of the series, Houston had home runs from [[George Springer]], [[Carlos Correa]], and [[Evan Gattis]] in their 7\u20133 win over Boston. [[J. D. Martinez]] had his 19th home run of the season, while [[Mookie Betts]] was placed on the 10-day [[disabled list]]. Trailing by a run entering the seventh inning of the third game of the series, the Red Sox rallied for three runs in the frame on the way to a 5\u20134 win. A two-run [[Andrew Benintendi]] homer provided the winning edge, while [[Dustin Pedroia]] was placed on the 10-day disabled list after appearing in only three games since making his season debut on May 26. In the closing game of the series, the Red Sox had 15 hits while [[Rick Porcello]] picked up his eighth win of the season in a 9\u20133 Boston victory. [[Brock Holt]] had three RBIs while Benintendi and [[Mitch Moreland]] both homered.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox split the series 2\u20132 (19\u201318 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 5\u2013June 7, vs. [[2018 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, [[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]] made a spot start,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://nesn.com/2018/06/red-soxs-alex-cora-explains-why-steven-wright-will-make-spot-start-tuesday/ |title=Red Sox's Alex Cora Explains Why Steven Wright Will Make Spot Start Tuesday |first=Adam |last=London |website=[[New England Sports Network|NESN]] |date=June 4, 2018 |accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref> and pitched seven shutout innings to get the win. [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[J. D. Martinez]] both had home runs in support of the 6\u20130 Boston victory; meanwhile, [[Drew Pomeranz]] was placed on the disabled list. Boston won the second game of the series, 7\u20131, as [[Andrew Benintendi]] and [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]] each had home runs; V\u00e1zquez went 3-for-4 with two RBIs and two runs scored. [[Jalen Beeks]] made his MLB debut as Red Sox starter in the third game of the series, yielding five first-inning runs to the Tigers, who went on to win, 7\u20132. Benintendi homered again for Boston, his 11th of the season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (15\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 8\u2013June 10, vs. [[2018 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]]'''<br />\n[[Chris Sale]] pitched eight innings while striking out ten and allowing just one run in the opening game of the series, but the Red Sox were unable to score and fell to the White Sox, 1\u20130. In the middle game of the series, home runs from [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] and [[J. D. Martinez]] led Boston to a 4\u20132 win, with [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] improving his record to 7\u20134. In the closing game, the White Sox held the Red Sox' offense in check, winning 5\u20132 and giving Chicago the series.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (6\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Boston Red Sox at Orioles 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Red Sox dugout, June 11 in Baltimore]]\n'''June 11\u2013June 13, at [[2018 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br />\n[[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]] shutout the Orioles for {{frac|6|2|3}} innings, but neither team could score and the first game of the series went to [[extra innings]]. In the 12th inning, the Red Sox pushed across two runs on [[sacrifice fly|sacrifice flies]], with [[Craig Kimbrel]] then closing out the win for his 21st [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the season. [[Mookie Betts]] returned from the [[disabled list]], batted leadoff, and went 1-for-5. In the second game of the series, [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] improved his record to 8\u20131 with the win. Boston's 6\u20134 victory included home runs from [[Rafael Devers]] and [[Andrew Benintendi]]. The two teams combined for 20 hits and 16 walks in a game that took nearly four hours to complete. The Red Sox completed the sweep with a 5\u20131 win in the third game of the series; [[Chris Sale]] was the winning pitcher while Betts and [[J. D. Martinez]] both homered.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (13\u20135 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez on June 9, 2015.jpg|thumb|right|[[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]]'s record stood at 9\u20131 after his win on June 17.]]\n'''June 14\u2013June 17, at [[2018 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]]'''<br />\nIn the series' opening game, starters [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] and [[F\u00e9lix Hern\u00e1ndez]] both went seven innings, with the Red Sox holding a 2\u20131 lead thanks to a sixth-inning home run by [[Xander Bogaerts]]. Neither bullpen allowed a run, with Red Sox closer [[Craig Kimbrel]] issuing two walks but getting his 22nd [[Save (baseball)|save]] of the season. In the second game of the series, [[Rick Porcello]] pitched six innings and left with the Red Sox ahead, 6\u20134. However, Seattle scored three runs off of the Boston bullpen, for a 7\u20136 win. All the Red Sox' runs came in the third inning, when they sent 11 men to the plate. [[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]], starter of the third game of the series, held Seattle to one run through seven innings, but Boston was limited to two hits and unable to score, as the Red Sox fell 1\u20130 to the Mariners. In the final game of the series, Boston jumped out to a 5\u20130 lead in the third inning and never looked back, winning 9\u20133. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] notched his ninth win of the season, while Bogaerts, [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], and [[Rafael Devers]] each homered.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox split the series 2\u20132 (17\u201312 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 19\u2013June 21, at [[2018 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]]'''<br />\nThe first game of the series was tied 2\u20132 going to the bottom of the eighth inning; the Twins then scored four runs\u2014two each off of [[Robby Scott]] and [[Joe Kelly (pitcher)|Joe Kelly]]\u2014as the Red Sox fell, 6\u20132. In the second game of the series, the Red Sox were held to one run on four hits, while the Twins were powered by home runs from [[Robbie Grossman]] and [[Max Kepler]], defeating Boston, 4\u20131. After being held to three runs in the first two games of the series, the Red Sox offense produced 16 hits and won the final game, 9\u20132. [[Rick Porcello]] improved his record to 9\u20133, while [[Mookie Betts]] and [[Andrew Benintendi]] both homered.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (12\u201312 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 22\u2013June 24, vs. [[2018 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]]'''<br />\nThe opening game of the series saw nine runs scored in the first inning, and Seattle led 10\u20135 entering the fifth inning. Boston outscored Seattle 9\u20130 the rest of the way, for a 14\u201310 win. Red Sox starter [[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]] gave up ten [[earned run]]s\u2014raising his season ERA from 1.23 to 3.38<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jd-martinez-ties-hr-lead-lifts-sox-to-win/c-282454954 |title=J.D. ties MLB HR lead (23), lifts Sox with 5 RBIs |first=Ian |last=Browne |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=June 22, 2018 |accessdate=June 22, 2018}}</ref>\u2014but escaped with a [[no decision]]. [[Nelson Cruz]] of the Mariners had two home runs and seven RBIs in a losing effort. For the Red Sox, [[J. D. Martinez]] went 4-for-5 with a home run and five RBIs, and every batter had at least one hit. In the second game of the series, Seattle again jumped out to an early lead, 5\u20130 after four innings. This time, there would be no Boston comeback, as it was 7\u20130 going to the ninth, with the Red Sox only scoring two late runs. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] took the loss, his first since May 15, and only his second of the season. In the closing game of the series, [[Chris Sale]] had 13 strikeouts while holding Seattle scoreless through seven innings. The Red Sox bullpen completed the shutout, while [[Mitch Moreland]] homered in support of the 5\u20130 win.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (21\u201317 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Rafael Devers.jpg|thumb|right|[[Rafael Devers]] was 5-for-5, including a [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]], on June 30.]]\n'''June 26\u2013June 28, vs. [[2018 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]]'''<br />\nIn the series' first game, Boston had a 5\u20130 lead after two innings and went on to win, 9\u20131. [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] improved his record to 9\u20135, while [[Mookie Betts]], [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], [[Christian V\u00e1zquez]], and [[J. D. Martinez]] each homered. In the second game of the series, the Red Sox jumped out to a 6\u20130 lead in the second inning. The Angels fought back to tie it, 6\u20136, in the seventh, with Boston then scoring three unanswered runs for a 9\u20136 victory. The two teams used a combined 12 pitchers, with Angels reliever [[Jake Jewell]] leaving the game after an apparent ankle injury suffered while trying to make a play at the plate.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadspin.com/angels-rookie-pitcher-jake-jewell-carried-off-on-stretc-1827194436 |title=Angels Rookie Pitcher Jake Jewell Carried Off On Stretcher After Awful Ankle Injury |first=Lauren |last=Theisen |website=[[Deadspin]] |date=June 27, 2018 |accessdate=June 27, 2018}}</ref> The Red Sox had home runs from Martinez, [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]], and [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]]. In the series' final game, [[Brian Johnson (pitcher)|Brian Johnson]] started and left after four innings with the Red Sox trailing, 1\u20130. [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]] then pitched two scoreless innings as Boston took the lead, 2\u20131, and was credited with the win as the Red Sox stayed ahead for a 4\u20132 final. [[Craig Kimbrel]] got his second consecutive save, bringing his season total to 24. Bradley Jr. and [[Rafael Devers]] both homered, as Boston completed the sweep. For the first time in franchise history, the Red Sox swept a season series of 5 or more games<ref>{{cite tweet|user=TomCaron|number=1012487136183046144|title=Hard to believe Sox have never swept the Angels in a season series. They've also never gone 6-0 against a team in the regular season. Longest season series they've swept is 4 games. #RedSox|first=Tom|last=Caron|website=[[Twitter]]|date=June 28, 2018|accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> and also set a major league record of 20 home run against a single opponent with 6 or fewer games played against in a season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (22\u20139 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''June 29\u2013June 30, at [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, New York built a 5\u20130 lead after four innings, en route to an 8\u20131 win. Boston starter [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] gave up five runs in six innings, taking the loss. The Yankees had four home runs, including two by [[Greg Bird (baseball)|Greg Bird]], while new Red Sox 1B/OF [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] was 2-for-4 in his debut game with the team. In the middle game of the series, a first-inning [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] from [[Rafael Devers]] put Boston up early, in a game they would go on to win, 11\u20130. Devers was 5-for-5 at the plate, lacking only a triple for the [[hitting for the cycle|cycle]]. [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] also homered for the Red Sox, while [[Chris Sale]] improved his record to 8\u20134.\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=July}}\n\n===July===\n'''July 1, at [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]] (cont.)'''<br />\nIn the third and final game of the series, the Yankees jumped on [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] early, scoring six first-inning runs. Price went {{frac|3|1|3}} innings, allowing five homers and eight runs. The Yankees had six home runs, including three from [[Aaron Hicks]], as they defeated Boston, 11\u20131.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (13\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 2\u2013July 4, at [[2018 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]]'''<br />\nIn the opening game of the series, [[Rick Porcello]] drove in three runs with a bases-loaded double in the second inning; he pitched six innings, limiting the Nationals to two runs on seven hits, and got the win, his tenth of the season. Boston's other run in the 4\u20133 final came on a [[Mookie Betts]] home run, with [[Craig Kimbrel]] notching his 25th save of the season. In the second game of the series, the Red Sox had a pair of three-run home runs from [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] and [[Xander Bogaerts]], plus a two-run shot from [[J. D. Martinez]], en route to an 11\u20134 win. On [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]], the third game of the series was scoreless through six innings, until Boston score twice in the seventh and once in the ninth, for a 3\u20130 victory to complete the sweep. [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] had two RBIs, while [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] captured his 10th win of the season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (18\u20137 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Andrew Benintendi on August 17, 2016.jpg|thumb|right|[[Andrew Benintendi]] went 8-for-11 with seven runs scored in the July 6\u20138 three-game series.]]\n'''July 6\u2013July 8, at [[2018 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]]'''<br />\nIn the series opener, the Red Sox scored four runs in the first, and another four in the second, jumping out early in what would be a 10\u20135 win. [[Mookie Betts]], [[J. D. Martinez]], and [[Xander Bogaerts]] each homered, while [[Chris Sale]] improved his record to 9\u20134. [[Tyler Thornburg]], acquired by Boston in December 2016 and out for the 2017 season due to surgery, made his Red Sox debut. The second game of the series was tied at four after five innings; the Red Sox then outscored the Royals 11\u20130, with Royals catcher [[Drew Butera]] facing six batters to record the final Boston out in the ninth, for a 15\u20134 final. [[Andrew Benintendi]] had a home run and a double, going 2-for-2 along with four walks, batting behind Betts who went 4-for-6. [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] had a [[no decision]], leaving after {{frac|4|2|3}} innings, with [[Heath Hembree]] picking up the win after pitching {{frac|1|1|3}} hitless innings in relief. In the final game of the series, [[Rick Porcello]] allowed nine hits in seven innings, but held the Royals to three runs and got the win, improving his season record to 11\u20133. Boston's three-run seventh inning was the difference in the 7\u20134 final score. Benintendi was 4-for-5 at the plate, while [[Craig Kimbrel]] recorded his 27th save of the year.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (32\u201313 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 9\u2013July 11, vs. [[2018 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]]'''<br />\nThe Red Sox' winning streak was extended to seven games with a 5\u20130 victory in the opening game of the series. Boston's runs came on a [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] two-run homer in the first, and a [[J. D. Martinez]] three-run homer in the eighth. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] improved his record to 11\u20133 for the season. In the middle game of the series, the Red Sox sent nine men to the plate in a five-run third inning, and won again, 8\u20134. Boston used six pitchers in the game, with reliever [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] getting the win; [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]], making a spot start, left after three innings. A 4\u20132 Boston win in the final game of the series completed the sweep, with [[Chris Sale]] improving his record to 10\u20134 for the season. [[Xander Bogaerts]] was 3-for-4 at the plate including a triple.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (17\u20136 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:2016-10-08 Xander Bogaerts 2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Xander Bogaerts]] hit his third [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] of the season on July 14.]]\n'''July 12\u2013July 15, vs. [[2018 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br />\nIn the opener of a four-game series, Boston scored all but one of their runs in the fourth inning as they defeated Toronto, 6\u20134, extending their winning streak to ten games. [[Mookie Betts]] hit the team's eighth [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] of the season, in a 13-pitch at bat\u2014a [[full count]] plus seven pitches fouled off<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadspin.com/mookie-bettss-13-pitch-grand-slam-at-bat-is-best-viewed-1827564084 |title=Mookie Betts's 13-Pitch Grand Slam At-Bat Is Best Viewed In Its Entirety |first=Lauren |last=Theisen |website=[[Deadspin]] |date=July 12, 2018 |accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref>\u2014as he went 2-for-4 with five RBIs. With a 66\u201329 record, the Red Sox reached 37 games over .500 for the first time since [[1949 Boston Red Sox season|1949]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/07/13/mookie-betts-red-sox |title=Mookie Betts, rolling Red Sox try for 11th straight win Friday |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=July 13, 2018 |accessdate=July 13, 2018}}</ref> Boston's winning streak came to an end in the second game of the series, a 13\u20137 loss to Toronto. The two teams used a total of 13 pitchers, as both starters only retired a combined 15 batters. Betts was 3-for-4 at the plate\u2014raising his average to .357 for the season\u2014along with a walk, two RBIs, and two runs scored. The third game of the series went to extra innings, after Boston scored the tying run in the bottom of the ninth on back-to-back doubles by [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] In the bottom of the tenth, the Red Sox loaded the bases on an error, a single, and an [[Intentional base on balls|intentional walk]]. Bogaerts then hit a [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] grand slam to win the game, 6\u20132. It was Bogaerts' third grand slam of the season and the Red Sox' ninth. Boston won the final game of series, 5\u20132, with Bogaerts again homering and [[Craig Kimbrel]] getting his 30th save of the season. The Red Sox reached the [[2018 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star break]] with MLB's best record (68\u201330, a .694 [[winning percentage]]) and a {{frac|4|1|2}} game lead over the Yankees in the [[American League East|AL East]].<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (24\u201321 runs)'''</small>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! July 17, [[2018 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] at [[Nationals Park]]\n|}\nIn an 8\u20136 American League win in 10 innings, four of the five Red Sox all-stars played in the game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/boxscore?gameId=380717132 |title=American League vs. National League |website=[[ESPN]] |date=July 17, 2018 |accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref> [[Mookie Betts]] started in right field and was 0-for-3 at the plate, while [[J. D. Martinez]] started at DH and was 1-for-2. [[Chris Sale]] was the AL starting pitcher, striking out one and allowing one hit in an inning of work. [[Mitch Moreland]] was 2-for-3 after entering the game at first base. Closer [[Craig Kimbrel]] did not play.\n\n'''July 20\u2013July 22, at [[2018 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]]'''<br />\nThe one and only run in the first game of the series came in the top of the first inning, when [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] drove in [[Andrew Benintendi]]. It was the Red Sox' first 1\u20130 win since the second game of the season. [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] pitched {{frac|6|1|3}} scoreless innings for the win, with [[Craig Kimbrel]] getting the save. Boston fell to Detroit in the second game of the series, 5\u20130, despite outhitting the Tigers, 8\u20137. Starter [[Brian Johnson (pitcher)|Brian Johnson]] took the loss, although both runs he allowed in five innings of work were [[Earned run|unearned]]. The Red Sox won the series' final game, 9\u20131, with [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] going 2-for-4 with three RBIs, while [[Chris Sale]] improved his record to 11\u20134.<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (10\u20136 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 23\u2013July 24, at [[2018 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br />\nA 5\u20133 win in the first game of the series gave Boston a 71\u201331 record, reaching 40 games over .500 for the first time since their [[1949 Boston Red Sox season|1949 season]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/recap?gameId=380723101 |title=Porcello throws 6 shutout innings as Red Sox top Orioles 5-3 |website=[[ESPN]] |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=July 23, 2018 |accessdate=July 23, 2018}}</ref> [[Rick Porcello]] pitched six scoreless innings for the win, while [[Mitch Moreland]] hit his 12th home run of the season. For the second game of the series, the Red Sox activated [[Drew Pomeranz]] from the [[disabled list]]; he took the mound for the first time since May 31. Pomeranz allowed four runs in {{frac|4|2|3}} innings, taking the loss as Baltimore prevailed, 7\u20136. Trailing 7\u20133 after five innings, Boston scored twice in the eighth and once in the ninth to nearly force extra innings. [[J. D. Martinez]] had two home runs, increasing his total to 31 for the season; [[Blake Swihart]] and [[Mookie Betts]] had one each. The third and final game of the series was postponed, due to rain. The Red Sox had jumped out to a 5\u20130 lead\u2014including home runs from Betts, Martinez, and [[Andrew Benintendi]]\u2014in two innings of play before the game was halted; however, those statistics are discarded, as the game will be replayed from the start.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/07/25/rain-washes-out-red-sox-os-game-3-red-sox-homers-wiped-off-the-board |title=Rain washes out Red Sox-O's game; 3 Red Sox homers wiped off the board |first=David |last=Ginsburg |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[Boston.com]] |date=July 25, 2018 |accessdate=July 25, 2018}}</ref><br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox split the series 1\u20131 (11\u201310 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:Nathan Eovaldi (June 2012).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Nathan Eovaldi]], seen here in 2012, got the win in his Boston debut on July 29.]]\n'''July 26\u2013July 29, vs. [[2018 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]]'''<br />\nMinnesota won the first game of the series, 2\u20131, with two late runs after Boston had gone out to a 1\u20130 lead in the second inning. The Red Sox threatened in the bottom of the ninth, loading the bases with two outs, with Twins closer [[Fernando Rodney]] striking out [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] to complete the save. In the second game of the series, Boston took a 2\u20130 lead in the fifth inning via a Bradley Jr. home run. The Twins got back one run in the seventh, and then scored two runs off of closer [[Craig Kimbrel]] with two outs in the ninth, to take a 3\u20132 lead. [[Rafael Devers]] forced extra innings with a home run in the bottom of the ninth, and [[Mookie Betts]] opened the bottom of the tenth with a [[walk-off home run]], giving the Red Sox a 4\u20133 win. Boston won the third game of the series, 10\u20134, with [[Rick Porcello]] improving his record to 13\u20134 for the year. Five Red Sox batters had two hits each, including [[J. D. Martinez]] who hit his 32nd home run of the season. Boston won the final game of the series, 3\u20130, with Martinez going 2-for-4 and driving in all three runs. Recently acquired starting pitcher [[Nathan Eovaldi]] made his Red Sox debut, allowing four hits in seven innings while striking out five and issuing no walks.<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20131 (18\u20139 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''July 30\u2013July 31, vs. [[2018 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]'''<br />\nThe first game of the series was tied 1\u20131 at the end of five innings, with no further scoring until the bottom of the 13th, when [[Blake Swihart]] drove in [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] for a 2\u20131 victory. All of Boston's hits came from the bottom four spots in the order, which went a collective 7-for-19. Philadelphia won the second and final game of the series, 3\u20131. Newly acquired second baseman [[Ian Kinsler]] made his Red Sox debut and went 1-for-4. [[Xander Bogaerts]] drove in Swihart for Boston's only run.<br/>\n<small>'''Red Sox split the series 1\u20131 (3\u20134 runs)'''</small><br />\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=August}}\n\n===August===\n[[File:2016-10-08 Andrew Benintendi.jpg|thumb|right|[[Andrew Benintendi]]'s extra-inning RBI in the fourth game of the series completed the Red Sox' sweep of the Yankees.]]\n'''August 2\u2013August 5, vs. [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the four game set, the Yankees jumped out to an early 4\u20130 lead, only to see Boston score the next 10 runs, including eight in the fourth inning, en route to a 15\u20137 final. Much of the offense came from the top third of the Red Sox order: [[Mookie Betts]] was 4-for-4 plus two walks, [[Andrew Benintendi]] was 3-for-6 with three RBIs, and [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] was 3-for-5 with six RBIs; all three of his hits were home runs. Pearce joined [[Kevin Millar]] and [[Mo Vaughn]] as the only Red Sox players to have a three-homer game against the Yankees.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/recap?gameId=380802102 |title=Yankees vs. Red Sox - Game Recap |website=[[ESPN]] |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=August 2, 2018 |accessdate=August 3, 2018}}</ref> In the second game of the series, [[Rick Porcello]] allowed only one run and one hit in a complete game effort, improving his record to 14\u20134 as the Red Sox won, 4\u20131. [[Alex Cora]] had been ejected in the bottom of the first inning, his first ejection as Boston manager, after taking exception to warnings issued to both dugouts. Boston then scored three runs, with two coming on a Pearce homer. [[Ian Kinsler]] had to leave the game due to injury, and was later placed on the disabled list; Betts replaced him at second base for several innings, his first time playing the position since 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.masslive.com/redsox/index.ssf/2018/08/mookie_betts_playing_second_ba.html |title=Mookie Betts playing second base for Boston Red Sox as Ian Kinsler exits game with left hamstring tightness |first=Christopher |last=Smith |website=masslive.com |date=August 3, 2018 |accessdate=August 4, 2018}}</ref> Boston won the third game of the series, 4\u20131, with [[Nathan Eovaldi]] allowing no runs and three hits in eight innings. [[Mitch Moreland]] and [[J. D. Martinez]] both hit home runs. The Red Sox completed the four-game sweep in a 10-inning, 5\u20134 win that was broadcast on ''[[Sunday Night Baseball]]''. A Betts solo home run put Boston ahead in the fifth inning; however, New York capitalized on a [[Xander Bogaerts]] error in the seventh inning to go ahead, 4\u20131. With that score, Yankees [[closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Aroldis Chapman]] came on in the bottom of the ninth, but struggled, striking out two and walking three. With the bases loaded, a Martinez single cut the lead to 4\u20133. A Bogaerts grounder then drew an errant throw from Yankees third baseman [[Miguel And\u00fajar]], allowing [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] to score the tying run. The game went to extra innings after Moreland struck out, with [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] retiring the side in order in the top of the 10th. In the bottom of the 10th, [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] hit a two-out single and advanced to second on a [[wild pitch]]. Betts was [[Intentional base on balls|intentionally walk]]ed, and [[Tony Renda]] made his Red Sox debut as a [[pinch runner]] for Le\u00f3n. Benintendi then singled to center, scoring Renda, to secure the win and complete the sweep.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 4\u20130 (28\u201313 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 7\u2013August 9, at [[2018 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br />\nThe first game of the series found Toronto leading, 3\u20131, when Boston scored four in the top of the eighth, including three on a [[J. D. Martinez]] home run, to take a 5\u20133 lead. Toronto then forced extra innings, with a run each in the bottom of the eighth and ninth innings. In the top of the tenth, Boston scored five runs, via homers by [[Mitch Moreland]] and [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] Toronto could only answer with two runs, for a 10\u20137 final and fifth consecutive Red Sox win. In the series' second game, Boston jumped out to a 4\u20130 lead after three innings, ultimately winning 10\u20135. [[Rafael Devers]] hit a home run in his first game back from the disabled list. Boston's winning streak then ended at six games, as Toronto won the final game of the series, 8\u20135. [[Rick Porcello]] gave up seven runs in four innings, taking the loss. Martinez hit his 35th home run of the season, while [[Mookie Betts]]' ninth inning homer completed [[hitting for the cycle|the cycle]], the first of his career and first of the [[2018 Major League Baseball season|2018 MLB season]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/recap?gameId=380809114 |title=Mookie monster! Betts homers in 9th to complete cycle |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |website=[[ESPN]] |date=August 9, 2018 |accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref><br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (25\u201320 runs)'''</small>\n\n[[File:J._D._Martinez_Boston_Red_Sox_August_2018_(crop).png|thumb|right|upright|[[J. D. Martinez]] was the first player to reach 100 RBIs in the [[2018 Major League Baseball season|2018 MLB season]].]]\n'''August 10\u2013August 12, at [[2018 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br />\nIn a game with 33 total hits, the Red Sox out-slugged the Orioles, 19\u201312, in the first game of the series. Trailing 8\u20135 after five innings, Boston scored six runs in the sixth, three in the seventh, and five in the eighth. [[Drew Pomeranz]], pitching out of the bullpen, got the win, while [[Brock Holt]] went 3-for-4 with three RBIs. Holt, [[Xander Bogaerts]], and [[Andrew Benintendi]] each homered. [[J. D. Martinez]] had two RBIs, giving him 101 for the season. The second game of the series\u2014the first game of a day-night [[doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] to make-up a July 25 rainout\u2014was won by Boston, 5\u20130. [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] pitched six shutout innings, while [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] hit two home runs and [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] also homered. In the second game of the doubleheader, Boston used seven pitchers en route to a 6\u20134 win. Martinez hit two home runs, giving him 37 for the season, while [[Craig Kimbrel]] recorded his 34th save of the year. Boston won the fourth and final game of the series, 4\u20131, with [[Chris Sale]] recording the win in his return from the disabled list. [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] homered, and Kimbrel picked up his second save in two days.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 4\u20130 (34\u201317 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 14\u2013August 15, at [[2018 Philadelphia Phillies season|Philadelphia Phillies]]'''<br />\n[[Rick Porcello]] pitched seven innings, holding the Phillies to two hits and one run, as the Red Sox won the opener of a two-game set, 2\u20131. Boston's runs came on solo homers by [[Sandy Le\u00f3n]] and [[pinch hitter]] [[Brock Holt]]. The Phillies won the second game, 7\u20134, their three-run seventh inning being the difference. [[Mitch Moreland]] had three RBIs on a bases-loaded double.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox split the series 1\u20131 (6\u20138 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 17\u2013August 19, vs. [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br />\nIn the opening game of the series, Tampa Bay scored three times in the top of the first inning, but was held scoreless for the rest of the game, as Boston won, 7\u20133. [[Xander Bogaerts]] had two doubles and a triple, going 3-for-4 with two RBIs. In the second game of the series, the Red Sox jumped out to a 4\u20130 lead after the first inning, in what would be a 5\u20132 win. [[J. D. Martinez]] hit his 38th home run of the season, and [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] improved his record to 13\u20136. Tampa Bay kept Boston scoreless in the closing game of the series, 2\u20130, as the Red Sox were held to two hits.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (12\u20137 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 20\u2013August 23, vs. [[2018 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]]'''<br />\nIn their first series with the Indians during 2018, Boston lost the first game, 5\u20134, after building a 3\u20130 lead through two innings. The Indians had three home runs off of Red Sox starter [[Rick Porcello]], who took the loss. In the second game of the series, Cleveland collected 13 hits en route to a 6\u20133 win, giving Boston their third consecutive loss for only the second time during the season, the first being in April. Starter [[Nathan Eovaldi]] took the loss. A five-run fourth inning helped Boston win the third game of the series, 10\u20134. [[Mitch Moreland]] had a home run, while [[Xander Bogaerts]] hit two. In the final game of the series, [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] pitched eight shutout innings, as the Red Sox won, 7\u20130. Boston sent 11 men to the plate in the fifth inning, scoring six times.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox split the series 2\u20132 (24\u201315 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 24\u2013August 26, at [[2018 Tampa Bay Rays season|Tampa Bay Rays]]'''<br />\nThis three-game series was played on [[Players Weekend]], when MLB players are allowed and encouraged to put nicknames on the back of their uniforms. For the opening game, the nicknames used by Boston's starting lineup were as follows:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/see-the-red-sox-players-weekend-nicknames-c289581714 |title=See the Red Sox Players' Weekend nicknames |first=Ian |last=Browne |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 9, 2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2018/B08240TBA2018.htm |title=Tampa Bay Rays 10, Boston Red Sox 3 |website=[[Retrosheet]] |date=August 24, 2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Order || No. || Player || Nickname || Pos.\n|-\n| 1 || 50 || [[Mookie Betts]] || MOOKIE || DH\n|-\n| 2 || 16 || [[Andrew Benintendi]] || BENNY || LF\n|-\n| 3 || 25 || [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] || LATE LIGHTNING || 1B\n|-\n| 4 || 28 || [[J. D. Martinez]] || FLACO ||RF\n|-\n| 5 || &nbsp;2 || [[Xander Bogaerts]] || BOGIE || SS\n|-\n| 6 || &nbsp;5 || [[Ian Kinsler]] || BOOTSIE || 2B\n|-\n| 7 || 36 || [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] || NUNIE || 3B\n|-\n| 8 || 23 || [[Blake Swihart]] || SWI || C\n|-\n| 9 || 19 || [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] || JBJ || CF\n|-\n| \u2013 || 76 || [[H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez (baseball)|H\u00e9ctor Vel\u00e1zquez]] || CABEZON || P\n|}\nBoston out-hit Tampa Bay, 13\u201312, in the first game of the series, but lost, 10\u20133. All of Boston's hits were singles, and the team had 11 men [[left on base]]. [[J. D. Martinez]] and [[Xander Bogaerts]] were each 3-for-5 at the plate. In the second game of the series, the Red Sox took a 1\u20130 lead in the second inning, but were then held scoreless as the Rays won, 5\u20131. In the closing game of the series, Boston was held to three hits, falling 9\u20131 to Tampa Bay, marking the first time the Red Sox were swept in a series during the season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 0\u20133 (5\u201324 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 28\u2013August 29, vs. [[2018 Miami Marlins season|Miami Marlins]]'''<br />\n[[File:Twins infielder Eduardo Nunez talks to reporters at 2016 All-Star Game availability. (28466896676).jpg|thumb|right|[[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] hit his ninth home run of the season against the Marlins on August 29.]]\nIn the first game of the series, Boston took a 4\u20131 lead into the eighth inning, when Miami scored five runs off of the Red Sox [[bullpen]]. Trailing 6\u20134, Boston then scored three in the bottom of the eighth to retake the lead, 7\u20136. In the top of the ninth, the Marlins tied the game at seven, with a run off of [[Closer (baseball)|closer]] [[Craig Kimbrel]]. The Red Sox then won the game in the bottom of the ninth when the Marlins were unable to turn a [[double play]] on an [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] ground ball, allowing [[J. D. Martinez]] to score on a throwing error. In the second and final game of the series, Boston trailed, 5\u20133, going to the bottom of the seventh, when they erupted for 11 runs on 12 hits. This marked the first time a major league team recorded hits on 12 consecutive [[at bat]]s in a single inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bosoxinjection.com/2018/08/30/red-sox-review-breaking-epic-11-run-inning-vs-marlins/ |title=Red Sox Review: Breaking down the epic 11-run inning vs Marlins |first=Sean |last=Penney |website=bosoxinjection.com |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> A [[Base on balls|walk]] and a [[sacrifice bunt]] occurred, but those are only considered [[plate appearance]]s, not at bats. The sequence was: single, double, single, double, double, sacrifice bunt, triple, [[Intentional base on balls|intentional walk]], single, single, single, double, single, single,<ref>{{cite tweet |user=SoxNotes |number=1035150607756210176 |title=In the 7th inning last night, the Red Sox became the 1st team in MLB history to record a hit in 12 consecutive at-bats in an inning |date=August 30, 2018 |accessdate=August 30, 2018}}</ref> followed by a ground ball yielding a [[double play]] that ended the inning. The Red Sox sent 15 men to the plate, with five batters collecting two hits each. [[Tyler Thornburg]] recorded the win in relief, with the final score being 14\u20136. Both [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]] and [[Mookie Betts]] hit home runs during the game.<br /> \n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20130 (22\u201313 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''August 30\u2013August 31, at [[2018 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]]'''<br />\nIn the opener of a four-game series, Boston fell behind, 4\u20130, until scoring nine unanswered runs; four in the seventh inning and five in the ninth inning. [[Ian Kinsler]] went 3-for-4, while [[Mookie Betts]] and [[J. D. Martinez]] both homered. [[Ryan Brasier]] notched his first MLB win, one of four Boston relievers who each pitched a scoreless inning. The second game of the series included a two-hour rain delay, as Boston was outhit by Chicago, 14\u20135, and lost the game, 6\u20131. Boston's only run was a homer by [[Andrew Benintendi]]. [[Xander Bogaerts]] was ejected for the first time in his career, following an eighth-inning strikeout.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/recap?gameId=380831104 |title=Red Sox vs. White Sox - Game Recap |website=[[ESPN]] |date=August 31, 2018 |accessdate=September 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{collapse bottom}}\n\n{{collapse top|title=September}}\n\n===September===\n'''September 1\u2013September 2, at [[2018 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]] (cont.)'''<br />\n[[File:BrandonPhillipsApril2016.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Brandon Phillips]] had a two-run home run in his Red Sox debut on September 5.]]\nIn the third game of a four-game series, [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] returned from the disabled list and got the win, striking out 12 in {{frac|5|2|3}} innings, as the Red Sox won, 6\u20131. [[Eduardo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], and [[Ian Kinsler]] each hit home runs. Chicago won the final game of the series, 8\u20130, as Boston was held to five hits, and did not have a runner advance past second base.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox split the series 2\u20132 (16\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 3\u2013September 5, at [[2018 Atlanta Braves season|Atlanta Braves]]'''<br />\nThe Red Sox won the series' opening game, 8\u20132, after holding a 3\u20132 lead at the end of seven innings and then scoring five unanswered runs in the final two frames. The two teams combined to use 14 pitchers; [[Brandon Workman]] got the win in relief. [[Ian Kinsler]] went 2-for-5 with three RBIs. In the second game of the series, Atlanta established an early 1\u20130 lead, but was held scoreless after the second inning, as Boston won, 5\u20131. [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] was 3-for-4 with three RBIs, and starter [[Rick Porcello]] improved his season record to 16\u20137. Boston completed the sweep in a come-from-behind victory in the third game of the series. Down 7\u20131 after seven innings, the Red Sox rallied for six runs in the top of the eighth to tie the game. After the Braves scored once in the bottom of the eighth on a solo home run by [[Freddie Freeman]], a two-run home run by [[Brandon Phillips]] in the top of the ninth gave the Red Sox a 9\u20138 lead. [[Craig Kimbrel]] closed out the win in the bottom of the ninth with his 38th save of the season. Phillips, who was making his Red Sox debut, was 1-for-3 with two walks, two RBIs, and three runs scored.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (22\u201311 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 7\u2013September 9, vs. [[2018 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]]'''<br />\nThe Astros won the first game of the series, 6\u20133, after being held scoreless through the first six innings. Starter [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] had 10 strikeouts in {{frac|6|1|3}} innings and was charged with two runs, although all of Houston's runs were scored with Red Sox relief pitchers on the mound. [[Xander Bogaerts]] hit his 20th home run of the season. The Astros won the second game, 5\u20133, after building a 5\u20131 lead through four innings. [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] took the loss, allowing five runs in {{frac|3|1|3}} innings, while Bogaerts again homered. Boston won the closing game of the series, 6\u20135, with [[Mitch Moreland]] hitting a walk-off RBI single in the bottom of the ninth to break a 5\u20135 tie. The Red Sox had built a 5\u20131 lead through five innings, only to see the Astros plate four runs in the sixth to tie the game. [[J. D. Martinez]] hit his 40th home run of the season, while Bogaerts was 4-for-4 with a walk and an RBI. [[Mookie Betts]] went 7-for-12 during the series, raising his average to .342 for the season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (12\u201316 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 11\u2013September 13, vs. [[2018 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the series, Toronto had a 2\u20130 lead through six innings, with Boston then scoring seven unanswered runs for a 7\u20132 final. [[Chris Sale]] returned from the disabled list, pitching the first inning as the Red Sox used seven pitchers in relief, with [[Ryan Brasier]] getting the win. [[Brock Holt]] hit a three-run pinch-hit home run, as the Red Sox became the first major league team to clinch a spot in the 2018 postseason.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/24648564/red-sox-clinch-playoff-spot-chris-sale-returns-pitch-one-scoreless-inning |title=Red Sox clinch playoff spot as Chris Sale returns to pitch one scoreless inning |website=[[ESPN]] |date=September 11, 2018 |accessdate=September 11, 2018}}</ref> Boston won the second game of the series, 1\u20130, with the game's only run coming on a [[wild pitch]] in the fifth inning. Starter [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] went seven innings while striking out seven, walking none, and limiting the Blue Jays to three hits. With this win, the Red Sox reached 100 wins for the first time since their [[1946 Boston Red Sox season|1946 season]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/red_sox/2018/09/david_price_red_sox_blank_blue_jays_for_100th_victory |title=David Price, Red Sox blank Blue Jays for 100th victory |first=Michael |last=Silverman |newspaper=[[Boston Herald]] |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=September 12, 2018}}</ref> In the final game of the series, [[J. D. Martinez]] hit his 41st homer of the season to tie for the MLB lead.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/xander-bogaerts-red-sox-sweep-blue-jays/c-294530682 |title=Bogaerts catalyzes sweep with Magic No. at 6 |first=Ian |last=Browne |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 14, 2018 |accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> Toronto scored twice in the top of the eighth inning to tie the game, 3\u20133. Boston went ahead, 4\u20133, in the bottom of the inning, with [[Xander Bogaerts]] scoring from third on an infield error. [[Craig Kimbrel]] then retired the Blue Jays in order for his 40th save of the season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 3\u20130 (12\u20135 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 14\u2013September 16, vs. [[2018 New York Mets season|New York Mets]]'''<br />\n[[File:Steven Wright on June 11, 2015.jpg|thumb|right|[[Steven Wright (baseball)|Steven Wright]] pitched three innings of scoreless relief on September 20, getting the win as the Red Sox clinched the [[American League East|AL East]] division title.]]\nThe Red Sox were held scoreless in the first game of the series, losing 8\u20130 as Mets starter [[Noah Syndergaard]] allowed only three hits in seven innings. In the second game of the series, Boston overcame a 3\u20131 deficit, scoring four runs in the fifth inning on two-RBI doubles by [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]] and [[Brock Holt]], for a 5\u20133 final. [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] was 3-for-4 at the plate, while [[Rick Porcello]] improved his record to 17\u20137 for the season. In the final game of the series, Boston scored three runs in the third inning, with two of those runs coming on a home run by Holt, en route to a 4\u20133 win. The Red Sox used a total of seven pitchers, with starter [[Chris Sale]] going three innings and getting a [[no decision]].<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (9\u201314 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 18\u2013September 20, at [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br />\nIn the opening game of the three-game series, Red Sox starter [[Nathan Eovaldi]] held the Yankees scoreless through six innings. However, his gem was wasted as [[Neil Walker (baseball)|Neil Walker]] hit a three-run home run off of [[Ryan Brasier]] in the seventh inning, and the Yankees went on to win, 3\u20132. New York took the second game of the series, 10\u20131, with first baseman [[Luke Voit]] going 4-for-4 at the plate including three RBIs on two home runs. Boston won the closing game of the series, 11\u20136, with homers from [[Brock Holt]], [[Jackie Bradley Jr.]], and [[Mookie Betts]]. The win gave the Red Sox the [[American League East]] division title, for the third consecutive season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.boston.com/sports/boston-red-sox/2018/09/21/red-sox-clinch-al-east-yankees |title=Red Sox clinch AL East title with win against the Yankees |first=Mike |last=Fitzpatrick |website=[[Boston.com]] |agency=[[Associated Press|AP]] |date=September 21, 2018 |accessdate=September 21, 2018}}</ref><br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (14\u201319 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 21\u2013September 23, at [[2018 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]]'''<br />\n[[Sam Travis]] and [[Tzu-Wei Lin]] hit their first major league home runs for Boston in a 7\u20135 victory in the opener, a game that saw [[Matt Barnes (baseball)|Matt Barnes]] pick up his sixth win of the season after starter [[Chris Sale]] pitched {{frac|3|1|3}} innings, giving up two earned runs and striking out seven. Cleveland won the second game of the series, 5\u20134, in 11 innings. [[Drew Pomeranz]] took the loss in relief, with [[Rafael Devers]] and [[Blake Swihart]] hitting home runs for Boston. The third game of the series was again an 11-inning Cleveland win, 4\u20133. [[Mookie Betts]] went 4-for-6, including his 31st home run of the season; [[William Cuevas]] allowed only one run in {{frac|5|1|3}} innings of relief, but took the loss.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (14\u201314 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 24\u2013September 26, vs. [[2018 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]]'''<br />\n[[File:Mookie Betts running 2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Mookie Betts]] joined the [[30\u201330 club]] with his 30th steal of the season, on September 26 against the Orioles.]]\nThe Red Sox won their 106th game of the season, setting a new franchise record, with a 6\u20132 victory in the opening game of the series.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mookie-betts-leads-red-sox-to-record-106th-win/c-295869190 |title=Sox win record 106th, clinch Majors' best mark |first=Brian |last=MacPherson |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 24, 2018 |accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> Starting pitcher [[Nathan Eovaldi]] allowed one run in five innings and got the win, while [[Mookie Betts]] hit his 32nd home run of the season. The second game of the series, postponed a day due to rain, saw the Red Sox score early and often, en route to a 19\u20133 victory. Baltimore starting pitcher [[Ryan Meisinger]] lasted only one-third of an inning while giving up five runs. [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] got the win for Boston, while [[J. D. Martinez]], [[Xander Bogaerts]], and [[Blake Swihart]] each had home runs and [[Rafael Devers]] went 4-for-5 including two homers and six RBIs. Betts had his 30th [[stolen base]] of the season, making him the 40th player in MLB history with at least 30 homers and 30 steals in a season, joining the [[30\u201330 club]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/red-sox-topple-orioles-with-big-milestones/c-296099292 |title=Sox reach several milestones in G1 rout of O's |first=Craig |last=Forde |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 26, 2018 |accessdate=September 26, 2018}}</ref> The Orioles won the final game of the series, 10\u20133, scoring seven unanswered runs after the game was tied at three at the end of the fifth inning, just their 3rd win against the Red Sox all season.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox won the series 2\u20131 (28\u201315 runs)'''</small>\n\n'''September 28\u2013September 30, vs. [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]'''<br />\nIn the first game of the final regular season series, the Yankees defeated the Red Sox, 11\u20136, after jumping out to an 8\u20130 lead after four innings. [[Steve Pearce (baseball)|Steve Pearce]] had five RBIs, including Boston's tenth [[Grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] of the year. New York's win gave them home field advantage for the [[2018 American League Wild Card Game]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/yankees-to-host-al-wild-card-game/c-296405798 |title=Yankees win, will host AL Wild Card Game |first=Bryan |last=Hoch |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 28, 2018 |accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref> New York also took the second game, 8\u20135, their 100th win of the season. [[Brock Holt]] homered for Boston. The Red Sox won the final game of the series and their regular season, 10\u20132. [[Xander Bogaerts]] and [[J. D. Martinez]] both homered, with [[Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez (left-handed pitcher)|Eduardo Rodr\u00edguez]] picking up the win as Boston used eight pitchers. [[Mookie Betts]] went 1-for-2 and finished the season with a .346 average, while Martinez finished with 43 home runs and 130 RBIs.<br />\n<small>'''Red Sox lost the series 1\u20132 (21\u201321 runs)'''</small>\n\n{{collapse bottom}}<!--keep at bottom of section-->\n\n==Postseason==\n===American League Division Series vs. [[2018 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]]===\n{{main|2018 American League Division Series}}\nBoston entered the Division Series as the top seed in the American League, facing New York, the [[2018 American League Wild Card Game|AL Wild Card Game]] winner. This was the first ALDS meeting between the teams (playoff structure before 2012 precluded teams in the same division from meeting before the Championship Series). After splitting the first two games at [[Fenway Park]], the Red Sox won the next two games at [[Yankee Stadium]], eliminating New York and sending Boston on to the ALCS.\n\nThe Red Sox' 16\u20131 defeat of the Yankees in Game 3, during a misty evening in [[The Bronx]], included two historical footnotes. Firstly, the fifteen-run margin of victory for Boston accounted for the Yankees' worst-ever postseason defeat.<ref>[https://www.si.com/mlb/2018/10/08/yankees-red-sox-alds-game-3-blowout-loss Yankees Endure Franchise's Worst Postseason Loss Ever as Red Sox Win 16-1 in Game 3]. [[SI.com]]. Retrieved October 9, 2018.</ref> The Red Sox failed to score in only the first, fifth, and sixth innings, and generated 7 of their 16 runs in the fourth inning, chasing starter [[Luis Severino]] and batting through the order. In addition, [[Brock Holt]] [[hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]], the first player ever to do so in an MLB postseason game, capping off his performance with a ninth-inning home run against catcher [[Austin Romine]], brought in to pitch when the New York bullpen was overtaxed.<ref>Polacek, Scott. [https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2799849-brock-holt-hits-1st-ever-postseason-cycle-in-red-soxs-blowout-win-vs-yankees Brock Holt hits first ever postseason cycle in Red Sox blowout win va. Yankees]. [[Bleacher Report]]. Retrieved October 9, 2018.</ref>\n[[File:Chris Sale in 2017 (37215240281) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.85|[[Chris Sale]] got the win at Fenway in Game 1.]]\n[[File:Xander Bogaerts vs Orioles 2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.85|[[Xander Bogaerts]] hit Boston's only home run in Game 2.]]\n[[File:Brock Holt on April 24, 2015.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.85|[[Brock Holt]] hit the first postseason [[hitting for the cycle|cycle]] in MLB history in Game 3.]]\n[[File:Rick Porcello on April 24, 2015.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.85|Boston starter [[Rick Porcello]] got the win in Game 4, sending the Red Sox to the [[2018 American League Championship Series|ALCS]].]]\n\n;Game 1, October 5 at Fenway Park\n{{linescore|\n|Date = Friday, October 5, 2018\n|Time = 7:32 pm EDT\n|Location = [[Fenway Park]] in [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]\n|Other = <!--{{convert|#|F|C}}-->\n|Road=New York|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=0|R4=0|R5=0|R6=2|R7=1|R8=0|R9=1|RR=4|RH=10|RE=0\n|Home='''Boston'''|HomeAbr=BOS\n|H1=3|H2=0|H3=2|H4=0|H5=0|H6=0|H7=0|H8=0|H9=X|HR=5|HH=8|HE=0\n|WP=[[Chris Sale]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[J. A. Happ]] (0\u20131)|SV=[[Craig Kimbrel]] (1)\n|HomeHR=[[J. D. Martinez]] (1)|RoadHR=[[Aaron Judge]] (1)\n|Attendance=39,059\n|BoxURL = https://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2018/month_10/day_05/gid_2018_10_05_nyamlb_bosmlb_1/boxscore_col.html\n}}\n\n;Game 2, October 6 at Fenway Park\n{{linescore|\n|Date = Saturday, October 6, 2018\n|Time = 8:15{{nbsp}}pm (EDT)\n|Location = Fenway Park in Boston, Massachusetts,\n|Other = {{convert|62|F|C}}, cloudy\n|Road='''New York'''|RoadAbr=NYY\n|R1=1|R2=2|R3=0|R4=0|R5=0|R6=0|R7=3|R8=0|R9=0|RR=6|RH=8|RE=0\n|Home=Boston|HomeAbr=BOS\n|H1=0|H2=0|H3=0|H4=1|H5=0|H6=0|H7=1|H8=0|H9=0|HR=2|HH=5|HE=1\n|WP=[[Masahiro Tanaka]] (1\u20130)|LP=[[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] (0\u20131)|SV=\n|HomeHR=[[Xander Bogaerts]] (1)|RoadHR=[[Aaron Judge]] (2), [[Gary S\u00e1nchez]] 2 (2)\n|Attendance=39,151\n|BoxURL=https://gd2.mlb.com/content/game/mlb/year_2018/month_10/day_06/gid_2018_10_06_nyamlb_bosmlb_1/boxscore_col.html\n}}\n