{"title_page": "Pipe Dreams (1916 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1916 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pipe Dreams\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = Will Louis\n| producer       = Louis Burstein\n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Kate Price (actor)|Kate Price]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|1916|11|16}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent film<br>English intertitles\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Pipe Dreams''''' is a 1916 [[short film|short]] [[comedy film]] featuring [[Oliver Hardy]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=faCTiHZS1VwC&pg=PA56&dq=%22Pipe+Dreams%22+1916+film+Oliver+Hardy#v=onepage|title=Almost Hollywood: The Forgotten Story of Jacksonville, Florida|first=Blair|last=Miller|date=April 22, 2019|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780761859949|accessdate=April 22, 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Kate Price (actor)|Kate Price]] - Maggie\n* [[Oliver Hardy]] - Babe (as Babe Hardy)\n* Joe Cohen - Butler\n* Edna Reynolds - Maid\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1916]]\n* [[Oliver Hardy filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0007187|title=Pipe Dreams}}\n\n[[Category:1916 films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1916 comedy films]]\n[[Category:1916 short films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:Comedy short films]]\n{{1910s-short-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1916 film}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Pipe Dreams\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| director       = Will Louis\n| producer       = Louis Burstein\n| writer         = \n| starring       = [[Kate Price (actor)|Kate Price]]\n| music          = \n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = {{film date|1916|11|16}}\n| runtime        = \n| country        = United States \n| language       = Silent film<br>English intertitles\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Pipe Dreams''''' is a 1916 [[short film|short]] [[comedy film]] featuring [[Oliver Hardy]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=faCTiHZS1VwC&pg=PA56&dq=%22Pipe+Dreams%22+1916+film+Oliver+Hardy#v=onepage|title=Almost Hollywood: The Forgotten Story of Jacksonville, Florida|first=Blair|last=Miller|date=April 22, 2019|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780761859949|accessdate=April 22, 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Kate Price (actor)|Kate Price]] - Maggie\n* [[Oliver Hardy]] - Babe (as Babe Hardy)\n* Joe Cohen - Butler\n* Edna Reynolds - Maid\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1916]]\n* [[Oliver Hardy filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0007187|title=Pipe Dreams}}\n\n[[Category:1916 films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1916 comedy films]]\n[[Category:1916 short films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:Comedy short films]]\n{{1910s-short-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pipe_Dreams_(1916_film)"}
{"title_page": "R.A. the Rugged Man", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Ruggedman}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = R.A. the Rugged Man\n| image            = R.A the Rugged Man at Hip Hop Kemp 2013.jpg\n| caption          = R.A. the Rugged Man in 2013\n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias            = \n| birth_name       = R.A Thorburn\n| birth_place      = [[Suffolk County, New York]], [[United States|US]]<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/R.A.+the+Rugged+Man/+wiki</ref>\n| occupation       = [[Rapping|Rapper]], [[Screenwriting|screenwriter]], [[Film direction|film director]], [[Film production|film producer]]\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| years_active     = 1992{{ndash}}present\n| label            = [[Nature Sounds Records]] {{small|(current)}} [[Jive Records]], [[Capitol Records]], [[Priority Records]] {{small|(former)}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Tech N9ne]]|[[Hopsin]]|[[Talib Kweli]]|[[Brand Nubian]]|[[Sadat X]]|[[Mac Lethal]]|[[Brother Ali]]|[[Kool G Rap]]|[[Eamon (singer)|Eamon]]|[[Vinnie Paz]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://ratheruggedman.net/}}\n}}\n\n\n'''R.A Thorburn''' better known by his stage name '''R.A. the Rugged Man''', is an American [[rapper]], screenwriter, film director and film producer.<ref>[http://nature-sounds.net/artists/r-a-the-rugged-man/ R.A. The Rugged Man]. Nature-sounds.net. Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref> He began his music career at age 12, building a reputation locally for his lyrical skills. R.A. signed to major label [[Jive Records]] at age 18, but his debut album, ''Night of the Bloody Apes'', was never released.<ref name=\"villagevoice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2009-11-10/music/r-a-the-rugged-man-abides//|title=R.A. the Rugged Man Abides|author=Ben Westhoff|date=10 November 2009|publisher=|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nSince then, he has worked with the likes of [[Mobb Deep]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Kool G Rap]], and [[Notorious B.I.G.]], as well as producers [[Erick Sermon]], [[Trackmasters]], [[DJ Quik]], [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]], [[J-Zone]], and [[Ayatollah (record producer)|Ayatollah]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} He was featured on all three of [[Rawkus]]'s Soundbombing albums, as well as the platinum-selling [[WWF Aggression]] album. After a brief stint on [[Capitol Records]] (during which he recorded another unreleased album, ''American Lowlife''), R.A. signed with independent label [[Nature Sounds]] and released his official debut, ''[[Die, Rugged Man, Die]]''.<ref name=\"aboveground\">[http://abovegroundmagazine.com/news/culture-news/03/03/r-a-the-rugged-man-releases-video-based-on-experience-with-jive-records/ Above Ground Magazine: ''R.A. The Rugged Man Releases Video Based On Experience With Jive Records'']</ref>  In 2013, R.A. released his second album, ''[[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]'' on [[Nature Sounds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinnottingham.com/2013/02/20/r-a-the-rugged-man-the-peoples-champ-prod-by-apathy/|title=R.A. The Rugged Man: The People's Champ [prod by Apathy] - KevinNottingham.com|author=Jeremiah|work=KevinNottingham.com|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his hip hop career, Thorburn has been active as boxing commentator and film critic.  He has contributed to [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']], [[King (magazine)|''King'']], [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']], ''Rides'', ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'',<ref name=\"xxlmag.com\">[http://www.xxlmag.com/bloggers/2009/10/it%E2%80%99s-a-beautiful-thing-being-ra-the-rugged-man/ It's A Beautiful Thing Being R.A. the Rugged Man] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114091456/http://www.xxlmag.com/bloggers/2009/10/it%E2%80%99s-a-beautiful-thing-being-ra-the-rugged-man/ |date=2011-01-14 }}. Xxlmag.Com. Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref>''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'', ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'', among others.  He wrote and produced the cult film ''[[Bad Biology]]'', and also hosts the web series \"Film School\" on [[MTV]]'s Film.com.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1992\u20132003: Beginnings ===\nIn 1992, Thorburn signed with [[Jive Records]], then in the mid-1990s signed with [[Priority Records]]/[[EMI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abovegroundmagazine.com/news/culture-news/03/03/r-a-the-rugged-man-releases-video-based-on-experience-with-jive-records/|title=R.A. The Rugged Man Releases Video Based On Experience With Jive Records|last=Hakes|first=Tyler|date=3 March 2011|publisher=aboveGround Media|accessdate=24 July 2013}}</ref> His contract was later absorbed by [[Capitol Records]] but he began recording [[independent record label|independently]] in the early 2000s. He has worked with MCs such as [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], [[Mobb Deep]], and [[Chuck D]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}  He was featured on all three of [[Rawkus]]'s Soundbombing albums, as well as the platinum-selling [[WWF Aggression]] album, performing the theme song for [[Chris Jericho]]. In [[Ego Trip (magazine)|''Ego Trip'']] Vol. 1, Issue 3, The Notorious B.I.G. was quoted as saying, \"And I thought ''I'' was the illest,\" when referring to Thorburn.<ref>[http://www.villagevoice.com/2009-11-10/music/r-a-the-rugged-man-abides/ R.A. the Rugged Man Abides \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Music \u2013 New York]. ''Village Voice'' (2009-11-10). Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref>\n\n=== 2004\u20132012: ''Die, Rugged Man, Die'', film cameos & magazine writing ===\nIn 2004 he released his first album ''[[Die, Rugged Man, Die]]''<ref>[http://365aay.com/y1d171/ 365 Albums a Year \u00bb Year 1, Day 171: R.A. The Rugged Man \u2013 Die, Rugged Man, Die (2004)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707062822/http://365aay.com/y1d171/ |date=2011-07-07}}. (2010-04-06). Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref> on the Brooklyn-based label [[Nature Sounds]]. Thorburn has cameos in several music videos including [[Havoc (Mobb Deep)|Havoc]] from Mobb Deep's ''I'm the Boss'', Sadat X's ''Throw the Ball'' and Masta Killa's ''Old Man'' featuring  [[RZA]] and [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]].\n\nThe October 2006 issue of ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'' featured Thorburn's verse on [[Uncommon Valor: A Vietnam Story]] as its \"Hip-Hop Quotable\" of the month{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} and HipHopDX named it as the \"Verse of the Year\"<ref>Hale, Andreas. (2007-01-01) [http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/interviews/id.693/title.2006-hiphopdx-awards 2006 HipHopDX Awards | Rappers Talk Hip Hop Beef & Old School Hip Hop]. HipHop DX. Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref> AllHipHop.com states that \"This record will be remembered most for R.A.'s robotic flow recounting his own father's story of war while absolutely murdering the beat.\"{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} [[Rolling Stone]] Magazine recently compared Thorburn's rap flow to that of a blue-eyed Biggie Smalls.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} When reviewing his song \"On the Block\", [[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe Magazine]] said, \"I love this song. It give me goosebumps. It's very inventive.\"{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn addition to his hip hop career, Thorburn wrote a monthly movie column for ''[[Mass Appeal Magazine]]'', was a contributor to The Ego Trip Book of Rap Lists (St. Martin's Press) and Ego Trip's Big Book of Racism (HarperCollins), and has written numerous articles for other magazines including [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']], [[King (magazine)|''King'']], [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']], ''Rides'', [[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]<ref name=\"xxlmag.com\" /> and ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]''.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nA [[horror film]] fan, Thorburn has written three screenplays with cult film director [[Frank Henenlotter]] and is writer-producer of the Henenlotter film ''[[Bad Biology]]''. The film has an original score by Josh Glazer (J. Glaze) with additional production by [[Prince Paul (producer)|Prince Paul]], and cameos by Playboy model [[Jelena Jensen]] and Penthouse Pet Krista Ayne. Thorburn is working on his directorial debut, a film based on his family, ''God Take, God Give''.<ref>[http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9728/title.r-a-the-rugged-man-talks-new-film-and-music-projects R.A. The Rugged Man Talks New Film And Music Projects]. (2009-08-31). Retrieved on 2013-04-17.</ref>\n\n=== 2013\u2013present: ''Legends Never Die'' ===\nThorburn's second studio album ''[[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]'' was released on April 30, 2013.<ref>\"OK-Tho.com's Top 20 Albums Of 2013\" http://www.ok-tho.com/2014/01/top-of-year-albums-of-2013.html</ref>{{better source|date=October 2017}} Guest appearances include [[Brother Ali]], [[Masta Ace]], [[Tech N9ne]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Hopsin]], [[Eamon (singer)]] and [[Krizz Kaliko]]. His first single of the album was 'The Peoples Champ'. The second single was \"Learn Truth' Feat. Talib Kweli. Upon release the album debuted at number 1 on the US Billboard [[Top Heatseekers|Heatseekers Albums]] chart, number 17 on the Billboard [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart, and at number 131 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 4,000 copies in the United States and ended up selling over 40,000 units worldwide to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1561262/ll-cool-j-scores-13th-top-10-on-top-rbhip-hop-albums|title=LL Cool J Scores 13th Top 10 on Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|work=Billboard |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> In 2016, Thorburn was featured on German rapper [[Kool Savas]] studio album [[:de:Essahdamus|''Essahdamus'']] on the song \"Wahre Liebe\".\n\n==Personal life==\nThorburn's father, Staff Sgt. [[Uncommon Valor: A Vietnam Story#John A. Thorburn|John A. Thorburn]], was a [[Vietnam veteran]] affected by [[Agent Orange]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} His brother Maxx was born handicapped and blind, eventually dying at the age of 10. Thorburn's sister, Dee Ann, died in 2007 at the age of 26. Thorburn tells his father's story in \"[[Uncommon Valor: A Vietnam Story]],\" from the [[Jedi Mind Tricks]] album ''[[Servants in Heaven, Kings in Hell]]''. John A. Thorburn died 7 January 2010 from cancer.<ref>[http://www.hiphopug.com/ra-the-rugged-man.html Hip Hop Underground] bio on [[R.A. The Rugged Man]] describes the tragic death of is family members</ref> Thorburn is of [[Germans|German]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and [[Sicily|Sicilian]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25867/title.r-a-the-rugged-man-says-justin-timberlake-is-not-the-epitome-of-talent-|title=R.A. The Rugged Man Says Justin Timberlake Is \"Not The Epitome Of Talent\"|author=HipHopDX|date=18 October 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThorburn has two children: Ella (born in 2016) and John A. Thorburn (born in 2017).\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|R.A. the Rugged Man discography}}\n; Studio albums\n* 2004: ''[[Die, Rugged Man, Die]]''\n* 2013: ''[[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]''\n* 2020: ''[[All My Heroes Are Dead (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|All My Heroes Are Dead]]''\n\n; Compilation albums\n*2009: ''[[Legendary Classics Volume 1|Legendary Classics Vol 1]]''\n\n; Unreleased albums\n*1994: ''[[Night of the Bloody Apes (album)|Night of the Bloody Apes]]\n*1999: ''American Lowlife''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n; EP's\n*1998: ''Poor People''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n;Mixtapes\n*2007 ''Ruff Rugged & Raw{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n*2010 ''Crazy Man (The Best, The Forgotten & The Worst)''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n*2011 ''Murderous Verses''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=4 style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Film\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| Show\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Role\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Notes\n|-\n|2008\n|''Three Thug Mice''\n|Vic\n|(Short)\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Bad Biology]]''\n|Ex-Boyfriend (As R.A. The Rugged Man)\n|Also Writer and Producer\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Damnation (film)|Damnation]]''\n|Film Crew Guy #1\n|(Short)\n|-\n|2013\n|''Skid Row''\n|John\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em<!--unused references|refs= \n<ref name=\"RapGenius\">{{cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=Verified Explanations from R.A. The Rugged Man|url=http://rapgenius.com/Ra-the-rugged-man-every-record-label-sucks-dick-lyrics|work=RapGenius|publisher=|accessdate=04 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TSS\">{{cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=TSS PRESENTS SMOKING SESSIONS WITH RA THE RUGGED MAN|url=http://smokingsection.uproxx.com/TSS/2007/12/tss-presents-smoking-sessions-with-ra-the-rugged-man|work=The Smoking Session|publisher=|accessdate=04 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"aboveGround \">{{cite web|last= Hakes|first=Tyler|date=March 3, 2011|title=R.A. The Rugged Man Releases Video Based On Experience With Jive Records|url=http://abovegroundmagazine.com/news/culture-news/03/03/r-a-the-rugged-man-releases-video-based-on-experience-with-jive-records/|work=aboveGround Media|publisher=|accessdate=04 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n-->\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://ratheruggedman.net}}\n\n{{R.A. the Rugged Man}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:R. A. The Rugged Man}}\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Horrorcore artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Stony Brook, New York]]\n[[Category:Priority Records artists]]\n[[Category:Rappers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Ruggedman}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = R.A. the Rugged Man\n| image            = R.A the Rugged Man at Hip Hop Kemp 2013.jpg\n| caption          = R.A. the Rugged Man in 2013\n| background       = solo_singer\n| alias            = \n| birth_name       = R.A Thorburn\n| birth_place      = [[Suffolk County, New York]], [[United States|US]]<ref>https://www.last.fm/music/R.A.+the+Rugged+Man/+wiki</ref>\n| occupation       = [[Rapping|Rapper]], [[Screenwriting|screenwriter]], [[Film direction|film director]], [[Film production|film producer]]\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| years_active     = 1992{{ndash}}present\n| label            = [[Nature Sounds Records]] {{small|(current)}} [[Jive Records]], [[Capitol Records]], [[Priority Records]] {{small|(former)}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Tech N9ne]]|[[Hopsin]]|[[Talib Kweli]]|[[Sadat X]]|[[Mac Lethal]]|[[Brother Ali]]|[[Kool G Rap]]|[[Eamon (singer)|Eamon]]|[[Vinnie Paz]]}}\n| website          = {{URL|http://ratheruggedman.net/}}\n}}\n\n\n'''R.A Thorburn''' better known by his stage name '''R.A. the Rugged Man''', is an American [[rapper]], screenwriter, film director and film producer.<ref>[http://nature-sounds.net/artists/r-a-the-rugged-man/ R.A. The Rugged Man]. Nature-sounds.net. Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref> He began his music career at age 12, building a reputation locally for his lyrical skills. R.A. signed to major label [[Jive Records]] at age 18, but his debut album, ''Night of the Bloody Apes'', was never released.<ref name=\"villagevoice\">{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2009-11-10/music/r-a-the-rugged-man-abides//|title=R.A. the Rugged Man Abides|author=Ben Westhoff|date=10 November 2009|publisher=|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nSince then, he has worked with the likes of [[Mobb Deep]], [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[Kool G Rap]], and [[Notorious B.I.G.]], as well as producers [[Erick Sermon]], [[Trackmasters]], [[DJ Quik]], [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]], [[J-Zone]], and [[Ayatollah (record producer)|Ayatollah]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} He was featured on all three of [[Rawkus]]'s Soundbombing albums, as well as the platinum-selling [[WWF Aggression]] album. After a brief stint on [[Capitol Records]] (during which he recorded another unreleased album, ''American Lowlife''), R.A. signed with independent label [[Nature Sounds]] and released his official debut, ''[[Die, Rugged Man, Die]]''.<ref name=\"aboveground\">[http://abovegroundmagazine.com/news/culture-news/03/03/r-a-the-rugged-man-releases-video-based-on-experience-with-jive-records/ Above Ground Magazine: ''R.A. The Rugged Man Releases Video Based On Experience With Jive Records'']</ref>  In 2013, R.A. released his second album, ''[[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]'' on [[Nature Sounds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinnottingham.com/2013/02/20/r-a-the-rugged-man-the-peoples-champ-prod-by-apathy/|title=R.A. The Rugged Man: The People's Champ [prod by Apathy] - KevinNottingham.com|author=Jeremiah|work=KevinNottingham.com|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his hip hop career, Thorburn has been active as boxing commentator and film critic.  He has contributed to [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']], [[King (magazine)|''King'']], [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']], ''Rides'', ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'',<ref name=\"xxlmag.com\">[http://www.xxlmag.com/bloggers/2009/10/it%E2%80%99s-a-beautiful-thing-being-ra-the-rugged-man/ It's A Beautiful Thing Being R.A. the Rugged Man] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110114091456/http://www.xxlmag.com/bloggers/2009/10/it%E2%80%99s-a-beautiful-thing-being-ra-the-rugged-man/ |date=2011-01-14 }}. Xxlmag.Com. Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref>''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'', ''[[The Ring (magazine)|The Ring]]'', among others.  He wrote and produced the cult film ''[[Bad Biology]]'', and also hosts the web series \"Film School\" on [[MTV]]'s Film.com.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 1992\u20132003: Beginnings ===\nIn 1992, Thorburn signed with [[Jive Records]], then in the mid-1990s signed with [[Priority Records]]/[[EMI]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abovegroundmagazine.com/news/culture-news/03/03/r-a-the-rugged-man-releases-video-based-on-experience-with-jive-records/|title=R.A. The Rugged Man Releases Video Based On Experience With Jive Records|last=Hakes|first=Tyler|date=3 March 2011|publisher=aboveGround Media|accessdate=24 July 2013}}</ref> His contract was later absorbed by [[Capitol Records]] but he began recording [[independent record label|independently]] in the early 2000s. He has worked with MCs such as [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], [[Mobb Deep]], and [[Chuck D]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}  He was featured on all three of [[Rawkus]]'s Soundbombing albums, as well as the platinum-selling [[WWF Aggression]] album, performing the theme song for [[Chris Jericho]]. In [[Ego Trip (magazine)|''Ego Trip'']] Vol. 1, Issue 3, The Notorious B.I.G. was quoted as saying, \"And I thought ''I'' was the illest,\" when referring to Thorburn.<ref>[http://www.villagevoice.com/2009-11-10/music/r-a-the-rugged-man-abides/ R.A. the Rugged Man Abides \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Music \u2013 New York]. ''Village Voice'' (2009-11-10). Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref>\n\n=== 2004\u20132012: ''Die, Rugged Man, Die'', film cameos & magazine writing ===\nIn 2004 he released his first album ''[[Die, Rugged Man, Die]]''<ref>[http://365aay.com/y1d171/ 365 Albums a Year \u00bb Year 1, Day 171: R.A. The Rugged Man \u2013 Die, Rugged Man, Die (2004)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707062822/http://365aay.com/y1d171/ |date=2011-07-07}}. (2010-04-06). Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref> on the Brooklyn-based label [[Nature Sounds]]. Thorburn has cameos in several music videos including [[Havoc (Mobb Deep)|Havoc]] from Mobb Deep's ''I'm the Boss'', Sadat X's ''Throw the Ball'' and Masta Killa's ''Old Man'' featuring  [[RZA]] and [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]].\n\nThe October 2006 issue of ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'' featured Thorburn's verse on [[Uncommon Valor: A Vietnam Story]] as its \"Hip-Hop Quotable\" of the month{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} and HipHopDX named it as the \"Verse of the Year\"<ref>Hale, Andreas. (2007-01-01) [http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/interviews/id.693/title.2006-hiphopdx-awards 2006 HipHopDX Awards | Rappers Talk Hip Hop Beef & Old School Hip Hop]. HipHop DX. Retrieved on 2011-05-30.</ref> AllHipHop.com states that \"This record will be remembered most for R.A.'s robotic flow recounting his own father's story of war while absolutely murdering the beat.\"{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} [[Rolling Stone]] Magazine recently compared Thorburn's rap flow to that of a blue-eyed Biggie Smalls.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} When reviewing his song \"On the Block\", [[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe Magazine]] said, \"I love this song. It give me goosebumps. It's very inventive.\"{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nIn addition to his hip hop career, Thorburn wrote a monthly movie column for ''[[Mass Appeal Magazine]]'', was a contributor to The Ego Trip Book of Rap Lists (St. Martin's Press) and Ego Trip's Big Book of Racism (HarperCollins), and has written numerous articles for other magazines including [[Vibe (magazine)|''Vibe'']], [[King (magazine)|''King'']], [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']], ''Rides'', [[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]<ref name=\"xxlmag.com\" /> and ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]''.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nA [[horror film]] fan, Thorburn has written three screenplays with cult film director [[Frank Henenlotter]] and is writer-producer of the Henenlotter film ''[[Bad Biology]]''. The film has an original score by Josh Glazer (J. Glaze) with additional production by [[Prince Paul (producer)|Prince Paul]], and cameos by Playboy model [[Jelena Jensen]] and Penthouse Pet Krista Ayne. Thorburn is working on his directorial debut, a film based on his family, ''God Take, God Give''.<ref>[http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9728/title.r-a-the-rugged-man-talks-new-film-and-music-projects R.A. The Rugged Man Talks New Film And Music Projects]. (2009-08-31). Retrieved on 2013-04-17.</ref>\n\n=== 2013\u2013present: ''Legends Never Die'' ===\nThorburn's second studio album ''[[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]'' was released on April 30, 2013.<ref>\"OK-Tho.com's Top 20 Albums Of 2013\" http://www.ok-tho.com/2014/01/top-of-year-albums-of-2013.html</ref>{{better source|date=October 2017}} Guest appearances include [[Brother Ali]], [[Masta Ace]], [[Tech N9ne]], [[Talib Kweli]], [[Hopsin]], [[Eamon (singer)]] and [[Krizz Kaliko]]. His first single of the album was 'The Peoples Champ'. The second single was \"Learn Truth' Feat. Talib Kweli. Upon release the album debuted at number 1 on the US Billboard [[Top Heatseekers|Heatseekers Albums]] chart, number 17 on the Billboard [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart, and at number 131 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], with first-week sales of 4,000 copies in the United States and ended up selling over 40,000 units worldwide to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1561262/ll-cool-j-scores-13th-top-10-on-top-rbhip-hop-albums|title=LL Cool J Scores 13th Top 10 on Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|work=Billboard |accessdate=May 30, 2013}}</ref> In 2016, Thorburn was featured on German rapper [[Kool Savas]] studio album [[:de:Essahdamus|''Essahdamus'']] on the song \"Wahre Liebe\".\n\n==Personal life==\nThorburn's father, Staff Sgt. [[Uncommon Valor: A Vietnam Story#John A. Thorburn|John A. Thorburn]], was a [[Vietnam veteran]] affected by [[Agent Orange]].{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} His brother Maxx was born handicapped and blind, eventually dying at the age of 10. Thorburn's sister, Dee Ann, died in 2007 at the age of 26. Thorburn tells his father's story in \"[[Uncommon Valor: A Vietnam Story]],\" from the [[Jedi Mind Tricks]] album ''[[Servants in Heaven, Kings in Hell]]''. John A. Thorburn died 7 January 2010 from cancer.<ref>[http://www.hiphopug.com/ra-the-rugged-man.html Hip Hop Underground] bio on [[R.A. The Rugged Man]] describes the tragic death of is family members</ref> Thorburn is of [[Germans|German]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and [[Sicily|Sicilian]] descent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.25867/title.r-a-the-rugged-man-says-justin-timberlake-is-not-the-epitome-of-talent-|title=R.A. The Rugged Man Says Justin Timberlake Is \"Not The Epitome Of Talent\"|author=HipHopDX|date=18 October 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThorburn has two children: Ella (born in 2016) and John A. Thorburn (born in 2017).\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|R.A. the Rugged Man discography}}\n; Studio albums\n* 2004: ''[[Die, Rugged Man, Die]]''\n* 2013: ''[[Legends Never Die (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|Legends Never Die]]''\n* 2020: ''[[All My Heroes Are Dead (R.A. the Rugged Man album)|All My Heroes Are Dead]]''\n\n; Compilation albums\n*2009: ''[[Legendary Classics Volume 1|Legendary Classics Vol 1]]''\n\n; Unreleased albums\n*1994: ''[[Night of the Bloody Apes (album)|Night of the Bloody Apes]]\n*1999: ''American Lowlife''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n; EP's\n*1998: ''Poor People''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n;Mixtapes\n*2007 ''Ruff Rugged & Raw{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n*2010 ''Crazy Man (The Best, The Forgotten & The Worst)''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n*2011 ''Murderous Verses''{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! colspan=4 style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\"|Film\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Year\n! style=\"width:170px;\"| Show\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Role\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Notes\n|-\n|2008\n|''Three Thug Mice''\n|Vic\n|(Short)\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Bad Biology]]''\n|Ex-Boyfriend (As R.A. The Rugged Man)\n|Also Writer and Producer\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Damnation (film)|Damnation]]''\n|Film Crew Guy #1\n|(Short)\n|-\n|2013\n|''Skid Row''\n|John\n|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em<!--unused references|refs= \n<ref name=\"RapGenius\">{{cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=Verified Explanations from R.A. The Rugged Man|url=http://rapgenius.com/Ra-the-rugged-man-every-record-label-sucks-dick-lyrics|work=RapGenius|publisher=|accessdate=04 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TSS\">{{cite web|last=|first=|date=|title=TSS PRESENTS SMOKING SESSIONS WITH RA THE RUGGED MAN|url=http://smokingsection.uproxx.com/TSS/2007/12/tss-presents-smoking-sessions-with-ra-the-rugged-man|work=The Smoking Session|publisher=|accessdate=04 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"aboveGround \">{{cite web|last= Hakes|first=Tyler|date=March 3, 2011|title=R.A. The Rugged Man Releases Video Based On Experience With Jive Records|url=http://abovegroundmagazine.com/news/culture-news/03/03/r-a-the-rugged-man-releases-video-based-on-experience-with-jive-records/|work=aboveGround Media|publisher=|accessdate=04 Mar 2013}}</ref>\n-->\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://ratheruggedman.net}}\n\n{{R.A. the Rugged Man}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:R. A. The Rugged Man}}\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Sicilian descent]]\n[[Category:Horrorcore artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Stony Brook, New York]]\n[[Category:Priority Records artists]]\n[[Category:Rappers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Underground rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "name_user": "Meandeminem", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R.A._the_Rugged_Man"}
{"title_page": "Aisin Gioro", "text_new": "{{hatnote|This family name uses [[Manchu name|Manchu naming customs]]. The sub-clan's name or \"muk\u016bn\" is ''Aisin'' and the clan's name or \"hala\" is ''Gioro''}}\n{{More citations needed|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox noble house\n|surname = Aisin Gioro<br />[[File:AisinGioro2.svg|25px]]\n|native_name      = {{zh |t = \u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85 }}\n|other_name       = \n|type             = [[Dynasty|Imperial House]]\n|coat of arms     =  Seal of Qing dynasty.svg\n|image_size       = 280px\n|image_coat = Seal of Qing dynasty.svg\n|country = [[Later Jin (1616-1636)|Later Jin]]<br />{{Flag|Qing Dynasty}}<br />{{Flag|Manchukuo}}\n|estates =[[Forbidden City]] ([[Beijing]])<br />[[Summer Palace]] ([[Beijing]])<br />[[Old Summer Palace]] ([[Beijing]])<br />[[Mukden Palace]] ([[Shenyang]])<br />[[Chengde Mountain Resort]] ([[Chengde]])\n|parent house = [[Qing dynasty]]\n|titles =\n* [[Khagan]] (of the Mongols)\n* [[List of emperors of the Qing dynasty|Emperor of the Great Qing]]\n* [[Emperor of China]]\n** [[Son of Heaven]]\n** [[Lord of ten thousand years]]\n** [[Grand Khan of Tartary]]\n* Emperor of [[Manchukuo]]\n* [[Khan (title)|Khan]] of the [[Later Jin (17th century)|Later Jin dynasty]]\n* Kundulun Khan\n* Chief of the Jianzhou Jurchens\n* [[Crown Prince|Imperial Prince]] ([[Taizi]])\n* [[Prince of the First Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Second Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Third Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Fourth Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Fifth Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Sixth Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Seventh Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Eighth Rank]]\n* [[Prince of the Jurgen Tribe]]<ref>http://www.royalark.net/China/manchu1.htm</ref>\n* [[Duke of the First Rank]]\n* [[Royal and noble ranks of the Qing dynasty|Duke Who Receives Grace]]\n\n|styles           = \"His/Her [[Imperial Majesty (style)|Imperial Majesty]]\"\n|founded          = {{Start date and age|1616}}\n|founder          = [[Nurhaci]]\n|final ruler      = [[Puyi]]\n|current head     = [[Jin Yuzhang]]<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/World/Heir-to-Chinas-throne-celebrates-a-modest-life/2004/11/26/1101219744548.html?from=moreStories Heir to China's throne celebrates a modest life], ''The Age'', November 27, 2004</ref>\n|deposition       = {{End date|1912}}\n|ethnicity        = [[Manchu people|Manchu]]\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|t={{linktext|\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85}}\n|s={{linktext|\u7231\u65b0\u89c9\u7f57}}\n|p=\u00c0ix\u012bn Ju\u00e9lu\u00f3\n|mnc=\u1820\u1873\u1830\u1873\u1828<br />\u1864\u1873\u1823\u1875\u1823\n}}\n\n'''Aisin Gioro''' was the [[Manchu people|Manchu]] ruling clan of the [[Later Jin (1616\u20131636)|Later Jin dynasty]] (1616\u20131636), the [[Qing dynasty]] (1636\u20131912) and, nominally, [[Manchukuo]] (1932\u20131945). The House of Aisin Gioro ruled [[China proper]] from 1644 until the [[Xinhai Revolution]] of 1911\u20131912, which established a [[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|republican government]] in its place. The word ''aisin'' means ''gold'' in the [[Manchu language]], and \"gioro\" is the name of the Aisin Gioro's [[Ancestral home (Chinese)|ancestral home]] in present-day [[Yilan, Heilongjiang|Yilan]], [[Heilongjiang|Heilongjiang Province]]. In Manchu custom, families are identified first by their ''hala'' (\u54c8\u62c9), i.e. their family or clan name, and then by ''muk\u016bn'' (\u7a46\u6606), the more detailed classification, typically referring to individual families. In the case of Aisin Gioro, Aisin is the ''muk\u016bn'', and Gioro is the ''hala''. Other members of the Gioro clan include [[Irgen Gioro]] (\u4f0a\u723e\u6839\u89ba\u7f85), \u0160u\u0161u Gioro (\u8212\u8212\u89ba\u7f85) and Sirin Gioro (\u897f\u6797\u89ba\u7f85).\n\nThe [[Jin dynasty (1115\u20131234)|Jin dynasty]] (''jin'' means gold in Chinese) of the [[Jurchen people|Jurchens]], ancestors of the Manchus, was known as ''aisin gurun'', and the Qing dynasty was initially named ([[File:amaga aisin gurun1.png|40px]]) ''amaga aisin gurun,'' or the [[Later Jin (1616\u20131636)|Later Jin dynasty]]. Since the fall of the Qing Empire, a number of members of the family have changed their surnames to ''[[Jin (Chinese surname)|Jin]]'' ({{zh|c=\u91d1}}) since it has the same meaning as \"Aisin\". For example, [[Puyi]]'s younger brother changed his name from Aisin Gioro Puren (\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85\u6ea5\u4efb) to [[Jin Youzhi]] (\u91d1\u53cb\u4e4b) and his children in turn adopt ''Jin'' as their family name.\n\n==Family generation names==\nBefore the founding of the [[Qing dynasty]], the naming of children in the Aisin Gioro clan was essentially arbitrary and followed no particular rules. The [[Manchu people]] originally did not use [[generation name]]s before they moved into China proper; prior to the [[Shunzhi Emperor|Shunzhi era]], children of the imperial clan were given only a Manchu name, for example [[Dorgon]].<ref>{{cite book|year=2001|publisher=University of Washington Press|quote=In the beginning, among the first couple of generations, Manchu men had polysyllabic personal names (e.g., Nurhaci) that in their native language may have been meaningful but when transliterated by sound into Chinese characters were gibberish; furthermore, they did not arrange their personal names in generational order, as Han often did.|location=|isbn=978-0-295-98040-9|page=55|title=Manchus & Han: ethnic relations and political power in late Qing and early republican China, 1861-1928|edition=reprint, illustrated|author=Edward J. M. Rhoads}}<!--|accessdate=March 2, 2012--></ref><ref>{{cite book|year=2001|publisher=Stanford University Press|quote=Manchu naming practices also differed when it came to naming the children of the same generation. Chinese practice, at least among elites, typically called for all children of the same lineage and same generation to share the same first character of the given name. All the brothers and cousins (or sisters and cousins) of the same generation would be identified by this character (sometimes called beifen yongzi), which greatly simplified the determination of re|location=|page=243|title=The Manchu Way: The Eight Banners and Ethnic Identity in Late Imperial China|edition=illustrated, reprint|author=Mark C. Elliott}}</ref>\n\nAfter taking control of China, however, the family gradually incorporated [[Han Chinese]] naming conventions.<ref>{{cite book|year=2001|publisher=Stanford University Press|quote=lationships within the linage. The Manchus were not so careful about this sort of thing... The Chinese practice of using the same first character for the given names of children of same generation was initially adopted during the reign of the Kangxi Emperor. The children of Kangxi all sported the same prefix-character, yin (written \"in\" in Manchu), and every generation afterward was marked by the same initial character (or, in Manchu, the same initial sounds) in the given name. While some Manchu families followed suit, many others did not, or did so inconsistently: for example, the brother of an early-eighteenth-century general, Erentei, was named Torio, while the Xi'an general Cangseli named his son Cangyung, using the same sound, \"cang\" (\"chang\" in Chinese), for his and the following generation.|location=|page=244|title=The Manchu Way: The Eight Banners and Ethnic Identity in Late Imperial China|edition=illustrated, reprint|author=Mark C. Elliott}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|year=2001|publisher=University of Washington Press|quote=With the imperial clan itself taking the lead, Manchus started to shorten their personal names to disyllabic ones (e.g., Yinzhen, for the future Yongzheng emperor), to adopt names that were meaningful and felicitous in Chinese, and to assign names on a generaltional basis. By the time of the Guangxu emperor (r. 1875-1908), all the males of his generation in the imperial clan had the character zai in their personal names, such as Zaitian (the emperor), Zaifeng (1883-1952; his brother and future regent), and Zaizhen (1876-1948; his cousin). By contrast, the previous generation had used the character yi (e.g., Yikuang, Yixin, and Yihuan), while the following generation used the character pu (e.g., the future Xuantong emperor Puyi [1906-67] and his brother Pujie [1907-94]).|location=|page=55|title=Manchus & Han: ethnic relations and political power in late Qing and early republican China, 1861-1928|edition=reprint, illustrated|author=Edward J. M. Rhoads}}</ref> During the reign of the [[Kangxi Emperor]], all of the emperor's sons were to be named with a [[generation name|generation prefix]] preceding the given name. There were three characters initially used, ''Cheng'' (\u627f), ''Bao'' (\u4fdd) and ''Chang'' (\u9577), before finally settling on ''Yin'' (\u80e4) over a decade into the Kangxi era. The generation prefix of the [[Yongzheng Emperor]]'s sons switched from ''Fu'' (\u798f) to ''Hong'' (\u5f18). Following the Yongzheng Emperor, the [[Qianlong Emperor]] decreed that all subsequent male offspring would have a generation prefix placed in their name according to a \"generation poem\", for which he composed the first four characters, ''Yong Mian Yi Zai'' (\u6c38\u7dbf\u5955\u8f09). Moreover, direct descendants of the emperor will often share a similar [[Radical (Chinese characters)|radical]] or meaning in the final character. A common radical was shared in the second character of the first name of princes who were in line to the throne, however, princes who were not in line to the throne did not necessarily share the radical in their name.<ref>{{cite book|year=2001|publisher=University of Washington Press|quote=In a further refinement of the generational principle, the second character in the personal name of each person in the direct line of succession contained a radical that distinguished these name from all others of their generation in the imperial clan. Thus, the tian character in \"Zaiyian\" and the feng character in \"Zaifeng\" shared the \"water\" radical; hiweverm the zhen in \"Zaizhen\" (written with the \"hand\" radical) did not, because as the son of Yikuang (Prince Qing), Zaizhen was not in the direct line of succession.|location=|isbn=978-0-295-98040-9|page=56|title=Manchus & Han: ethnic relations and political power in late Qing and early republican China, 1861-1928|edition=reprint, illustrated|author=Edward J. M. Rhoads}}<!--|accessdate=March 2, 2012--></ref> In one case, the Yongzheng Emperor changed the generation code of his brothers as a way of keeping his own name unique. Such practices apparently ceased to exist after the [[Daoguang Emperor|Daoguang era]].\n\n===List of generation prefixes===\nThe latest additions to the list were the last 12 characters, taken from a \"generation poem\" composed by [[Puyi]] in 1938.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! Order !! Generation prefix !! [[Radical (Chinese characters)|Radical]] code !! Examples\n|-\n| [[Yongzheng Emperor]] || ''Yin'' (\u80e4; ''y\u00ecn''), ''Yun'' (\u5141; ''y\u01d4n'') || ''Shi'' (\u793a; ''sh\u00ec'') || [[Yongzheng Emperor|Yinzhen]], [[Yunreng]], [[Yunsi]], [[Yinxiang, Prince Yi|Yunxiang]], [[Yunti, Prince Xun|Yunti]]\n|-\n| [[Qianlong Emperor]] || ''Hong'' (\u5f18; ''h\u00f3ng'') || ''Ri'' (\u65e5; ''r\u00ec'') || [[Qianlong Emperor|Hongli]], [[Hongzhou (prince)|Hongzhou]]\n|-\n| [[Jiaqing Emperor]] || ''Yong'' (\u6c38/\u9852; ''y\u01d2ng'') || ''Yu'' (\u7389; ''y\u00f9'') || [[Jiaqing Emperor|Yongyan]], [[Yongqi, Prince Rong|Yongqi]]\n|-\n| [[Daoguang Emperor]] || ''Mian'' (\u7dbf; ''mi\u00e1n''), ''Min'' (\u65fb; ''m\u01d0n'') || ''Xin'' (\u5fc3; ''x\u012bn'') || [[Daoguang Emperor|Minning]], [[Mianyu]]\n|-\n| [[Xianfeng Emperor]] || ''Yi'' (\u5955; ''y\u00ec'') || ''Yan'' (\u8a00; ''y\u00e1n'') || [[Xianfeng Emperor|Yizhu]], [[Yicong]], [[Prince Gong|Yixin]], [[Yixuan, Prince Chun|Yixuan]], [[Yikuang]]\n|-\n| [[Tongzhi Emperor]] / [[Guangxu Emperor]] || ''Zai'' (\u8f09; ''z\u00e0i/z\u01cei'') || ''Shui'' (\u6c34; ''shu\u01d0'') || [[Zaixun, Prince Zhuang|Zaixun]], [[Tongzhi Emperor|Zaichun]], [[Guangxu Emperor|Zaitian]], [[Zaifeng, Prince Chun|Zaifeng]], [[Zaitao]], [[Zaiyi]], [[Zaixun, Prince Rui|Zaixun]]\n|-\n| [[Puyi|Xuantong Emperor]] || ''Pu'' (\u6ea5; ''p\u01d4'') || ''Ren'' (\u4eba; ''r\u00e9n'') || [[Puyi]], [[Pujie]], [[Jin Youzhi|Puren]], [[Puru (artist)|Puru]]\n|-\n|rowspan=19| N/A || ''Yu'' (\u6bd3; ''y\u00f9'') || ''Shan'' (\u5c71; ''sh\u0101n'') || [[Yuzhan]], [[Yuyan]]\n|-\n| ''Heng'' (\u6046; ''h\u00e9ng'') || ''Jin'' (\u91d1; ''j\u012bn'') || [[Jin Guangping|Hengxu]]\n|-\n| ''Qi'' (\u555f; ''q\u01d0'') ||  || [[Jin Qicong|Qicong]], [[Qigong (artist)|Qigong]]\n|-\n| ''Dao'' (\u7118; ''d\u00e0o'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Kai'' (\u95d3; ''k\u01cei'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Zeng'' (\u589e; ''z\u0113ng'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Qi'' (\u797a; ''q\u00ed'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Jing'' (\u656c; ''j\u00ecng'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Zhi'' (\u5fd7; ''zh\u00ec'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Kai'' (\u958b; ''k\u0101i'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Rui'' (\u745e; ''ru\u00ec'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Xi'' (\u932b; ''x\u012b'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Ying'' (\u82f1; ''y\u012bng'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Yuan'' (\u6e90; ''yu\u00e1n'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Sheng'' (\u76db; ''sh\u00e8ng'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Zheng'' (\u6b63; ''zh\u00e8ng'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Zhao'' (\u5146; ''zh\u00e0o'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Mao'' (\u61cb; ''m\u00e0o'') ||  || \n|-\n| ''Xiang'' (\u7965; ''xi\u00e1ng'') ||  || \n|}\n\n==Origins==\nThe Aisin Gioro clan, as a Manchu clan, claimed descent from the [[Jurchen people]], who founded the [[Jin dynasty (1115\u20131234)|Jin dynasty]] nearly five centuries earlier under the [[Wanyan|Wanyan clan]]. However, the Aisin Gioro and Wanyan clans are unrelated.<ref>\u6eff\u6d32\u6e90\u6d41\u8003 Qing ding Man Zhou Yuan Liu Kao,  \u672c\u671d\u8005\u8b02\u96d6\u8207\u5927\u91d1\u4ff1\u5728\u6771\u65b9\u800c\u975e\u5176\u540c\u90e8\u5247\u6240\u898b\u6b8a\u5c0f\u6211\u671d\u5f97\u59d3\u66f0\u611b\u65b0\u89ba\u7f85\u6c0f\u570b\u8a9e\u8b02\u91d1\u66f0\u611b\u65b0\u53ef\u70ba\u91d1\u6e90\u540c\u6d3e\u4e4b\u8a3c\u76d6\u6211\u671d\u5728\u5927\u91d1\u6642\u672a\u5617\u975e\u5b8c\u9854\u6c0f\u4e4b\u670d\u5c6c\u7336\u4e4b\u5b8c\u9854 \u6c0f\u5728\u4eca\u65e5\u7686\u70ba\u6211\u671d\u4e4b\u81e3</ref> It was explicitly said \"''we are not the scions of the previous Jin emperors.''\" by the Manchu leader Huangtaiji<ref name=\"Harrell2013\">{{cite book|author=Stevan Harrell|title=Cultural Encounters on China's Ethnic Frontiers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WChrSv86uIsC&pg=PA190#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 January 2013|publisher=University of Washington Press|isbn=978-0-295-80408-8|pages=190\u2013}}</ref> to the Ming.<ref name=\"ThomasHumphrey1996\">{{cite book|author1=Nicholas Thomas|author2=Caroline Humphrey|title=Shamanism, History, and the State|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3_inrj3puRQC&pg=PA209#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=1996|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-08401-2|pages=209\u2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Aisin Gioro claimed that their progenitor, [[Buk\u016bri Yong\u0161on]]<ref name=\"Crossley2000\">{{cite book|author=Pamela Kyle Crossley|title=A Translucent Mirror: History and Identity in Qing Imperial Ideology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wn4iv_RJv8oC&pg=PA198#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 February 2000|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-92884-8|pages=198\u2013}}</ref> (\u5e03\u5eab\u91cc\u96cd\u9806), was conceived from a virgin birth. According to the legend, three heavenly maidens, namely Enggulen (\u6069\u53e4\u502b), Jenggulen (\u6b63\u53e4\u502b) and Fekulen (\u4f5b\u5eab\u502b), were bathing at a lake called Bulh\u016bri Omo near the [[Changbai Mountains]]. A magpie dropped a piece of red fruit near Fekulen, who ate it. She then became pregnant with Buk\u016bri Yong\u0161on.\n\nThe Aisin Gioro also claimed descent from [[Mentemu]] of the Odoli clan, who served as [[List of Chieftains of the Jurchens#List of Jurchen chieftains during the Ming dynasty (1368\u20131644)|chieftains]] of the [[Jianzhou Jurchens]].\n\nThe Jianzhou Jurchen originate partially from the Huligai who were classified by the Liao dynasty as a separate ethnicity from the Jurchen people who founded the Jin dynasty and were classified as separate from Jurchens during the Yuan dynasty. Their home was in the lower reaches of the Songhuajiang river and Mudanjiang. The Huligai later moved west and became a major component of the Jianzhou Jurchens led by Mentemu during the Ming dynasty, and the Jianzhou Jurchens later became Manchus. The Jurchens during the Ming dynasty lived in Jilin. It was in the Ming dynasty the term Jurchen was expanded and referred to a wide variety of different peoples in Heilongjiang. The Aisin Gioro are not the same Jurchens as the ones who founded the Jin.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lszj.com/zhongguoshiji/jinwangchaolishi/33859.html |title=\u540e\u91d1\u671d\u4ecb\u7ecd\uff1a\u540e\u91d1\u7684\u7956\u5148\u662f\u8c01\uff1f\u4ec0\u4e48\u65cf\u4eba\uff1f |date=2016-09-01 |website=\u4e2d\u56fd\u5386\u53f2_\u5386\u53f2\u4eba\u7269\u5927\u5168_\u4e2d\u56fd\u5386\u53f2\u671d\u4ee3_\u5386\u53f2\u6545\u4e8b\u5927\u5168- \u5386\u53f2\u4e4b\u5bb6\u7f51 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511150027/https://www.lszj.com/zhongguoshiji/jinwangchaolishi/33859.html |archive-date=2018-05-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe Taowen, Huligai, and Wodolian Jurchen tribes lived in the area of Heilongjiang in Yilan during the Yuan dynasty when it was part of Liaoyang province and governed as a circuit. These tribes became the Jianzhou Jurchens in the Ming dynasty and the Taowen and Wodolian were mostly real Jurchens. In the Jin dynasy, the Jin Jurchens did not regard themselves as the same ethnicity as the Hurka people who became the Huligai. [[Uriankhai|Uriangqa]] was used as a name in the 1300s by Jurchen migrants in Korea from Ilantumen because the Uriangqa influenced the people at Ilantumen.<ref>{{cite book|title=Ch\u02bbing-shih Wen-t\u02bbi|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xrIzAAAAMAAJ&q=huligai&dq=huligai|year=1983|publisher=Ch\u02bbing-shih wen-t\u02bbi|page=33}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Ch'ing-shih Wen-t'i|url=https://books.google.com/?id=8GkUAQAAIAAJ&q=huligai&dq=huligai|year=1983|publisher=Ch'ing-shih wen-t'i|page=33}}</ref><ref name=\"Crossley2000\"/> Bokujiang, Tuowulian, Woduolian, Huligai, Taowan separately made up 10,000 households and were the divisions used by the Yuan dynasty to govern the people along the Wusuli river and Songhua area.<ref name=\"Ma1989\">{{cite book|author=Yin Ma|title=China's minority nationalities|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iuwMAQAAMAAJ&q=huligai&dq=huligai|year=1989|publisher=Foreign Languages Press|isbn=978-0-8351-1952-8|page=46}}</ref><ref name=\"Dmochowski2001\">{{cite book|author=Tadeusz Dmochowski|title=Rosyjsko-chi\u0144skie stosunki polityczne: XVII-XIX w|url=https://books.google.com/?id=vBsXAQAAIAAJ&q=huligai&dq=huligai|year=2001|publisher=Wydawn. Univ.|isbn=978-83-7017-986-1|page=81}}</ref> In the Jin dynasty the [[Huining Prefecture|Shangjing]] route (\u4e0a\u4eac\u8def) governed the Huligai.<ref>{{cite book|title=\u0131\u0303\u01af\u0304\u01af\u0306\u02ba\u0304\u00f8\u0304\u02bb\u0304\u030c: The Liao dynasty and Northern Song dynasty period, the Jin dynasty and Southern Song dynasty period|url=https://books.google.com/?id=xHHUbLSvle0C&q=huligai&dq=huligai|publisher=\u0304\u02bb\u0304\u0304\u00f0 \u0307 \u00de\u0307|volume=Volume 6 of \u0131\u0303\u01af\u0304\u01af\u0306\u02ba\u0304\u00f8\u0304\u02bb\u0304\u030c, \u02bb\u0308\u01af\u0304\u0153\u266d\u030c\u00de}}</ref> A Huligai route was created as well by the Jin.<ref name=\"\u9ed1\u9f99\u6c5f\u7701\u4ea4\u901a\u53851999\">{{cite book|author=\u9ed1\u9f99\u6c5f\u7701\u4ea4\u901a\u5385|title=\u4e2d\u56fd\u4ea4\u901a\u4e94\u5341\u5e74\u6210\u5c31: \u9ed1\u9f99\u6c5f\u5377|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Hdq6AAAAIAAJ&q=huligai&dq=huligai|year=1999|publisher=\u4eba\u6c11\u4ea4\u901a\u51fa\u7248\u793e|page=22}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=China Archaeology & Art Digest|url=https://books.google.com/?id=M0zrAAAAMAAJ&q=huligai&dq=huligai|year=1999|publisher=Art Text (HK) Pty Limited|page=205}}</ref><ref name=\"ZhuZhang2016\">{{cite book|last1=Zhu|first1=Ruixi|last2=Zhang|first2=Bangwei|last3=Liu|first3=Fusheng|last4=Cai|first4=Chongbang|last5=Wang|first5=Zengyu|title=A Social History of Medieval China|url=https://books.google.com/?id=40elDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA524&dq=huligai|date=22 December 2016|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-16786-5|pages=524\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Tikhvinski\u012dPerelomov1981\">{{cite book|author1=Serge\u012d Leonidovich Tikhvinski\u012d|author2=Leonard Sergeevich Perelomov|title=China and Her Neighbours, from Ancient Times to the Middle Ages: A Collection of Essays|url=https://books.google.com/?id=phhxAAAAMAAJ&q=huligai&dq=huligai|year=1981|publisher=Progress Publishers|page=201}}</ref>\n\nWhen the Jurchens were reorganized by Nurhaci into the Eight Banners, many Manchu clans were artificially created as a group of unrelated people founded a new Manchu clan (mukun) using a geographic origin name such as a toponym for their hala (clan name).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sneath |first1=David |title=The Headless State: Aristocratic Orders, Kinship Society, and Misrepresentations of Nomadic Inner Asia |date=2007 |publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=978-0231511674 |pages=99\u2013100 |edition=illustrated |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kWMaAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT113}}</ref> The irregularities over Jurchen and Manchu clan origin led to the Qing trying to document and systemize the creation of histories for Manchu clans, including manufacturing an entire legend around the origin of the Aisin Gioro clan by taking mythology from the northeast.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Crossley |first1=Pamela Kyle |title=Orphan Warriors: Three Manchu Generations and the End of the Qing World |date=1991 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0691008779 |page=33 |edition=illustrated, reprint |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NUTE8V-WhwoC&pg=PA33}}</ref>\n\n===Expansion under Nurhaci and Hong Taiji===\nUnder [[Nurhaci]] and his son [[Hong Taiji]], the Aisin Gioro clan of the Jianzhou tribe won hegemony among the rival Jurchen tribes of the northeast, then through warfare and alliances extended its control into [[Inner Mongolia]]. Nurhachi created large, permanent civil-military units called \"[[Eight Banners|banners]]\" to replace the small hunting groups used in his early campaigns. A banner was composed of smaller companies; it included some 7,500 warriors and their households, including slaves, under the command of a chieftain. Each banner was identified by a coloured flag that was yellow, white, blue, or red, either plain or with a border design. Originally there were four, then eight, Manchu banners; new banners were created as the Manchu conquered new regions, and eventually there were Manchu, Mongol, and Chinese banners, eight for each ethnic group. By 1648, less than one-sixth of the bannermen were actually of Manchu ancestry. The [[Qing conquest of the Ming|Manchu conquest of the Ming dynasty]] was thus achieved with a multiethnic army led by Manchu nobles and Han Chinese generals. Han Chinese soldiers were organised into the Army of the Green Standard, which became a sort of imperial constabulary force posted throughout China and on the frontiers.\n\nThe change of the name from Jurchen to Manchu was made to hide the fact that the ancestors of the Manchus, the Jianzhou Jurchens, were ruled by the Chinese.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Hummel |editor1-first=Arthur W. |chapter=Abahai |title=Eminent Chinese of the Ch'ing Period, 1644-1912 (2 vols) |date=2010 |publisher=Global Oriental |isbn=978-9004218017 |page=2 |edition=reprint |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0_V5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA2&#v=onepage&qf=false}} [http://www.dartmouth.edu/~qing/WEB/ABAHAI.html Via Dartmouth.edu]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Grossnick |first1=Roy A. |title=Early Manchu Recruitment of Chinese Scholar-officials |date=1972 |publisher=University of Wisconsin--Madison |page=10 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=RpdRAAAAMAAJ&q=In+1635,+doubtless+on+the+advice+of+his+Chinese+councilors,+Abahai+forbade+the+use+of+the+names,&dq=In+1635,+doubtless+on+the+advice+of+his+Chinese+councilors,+Abahai+forbade+the+use+of+the+names,}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Till |first1=Barry |title=The Manchu era (1644-1912): arts of China's last imperial dynasty |date=2004 |publisher=Art Gallery of Greater Victoria |page=5 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=XUVJAQAAIAAJ&q=In+1635,+doubtless+on+the+advice+of+his+Chinese+councilors,+Abahai+forbade+the+use+of+the+names,&dq=In+1635,+doubtless+on+the+advice+of+his+Chinese+councilors,+Abahai+forbade+the+use+of+the+names,}}</ref> The Qing dynasty carefully hid the 2 original editions of the books of \"''Qing Taizu Wu Huangdi Shilu''\" and the \"''Manzhou Shilu Tu''\" (Taizu Shilu Tu) in the Qing palace, forbidden from public view because they showed that the Manchu Aisin Gioro family had been ruled by the Ming dynasty.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Hummel |editor1-first=Arthur W. |chapter=Nurhaci |title=Eminent Chinese of the Ch'ing Period, 1644-1912 (2 vols) |date=2010 |publisher=Global Oriental |isbn=978-9004218017 |page=598 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0_V5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA598#v=onepage&q&f=false |edition=reprint}} [http://www.dartmouth.edu/~qing/WEB/NURHACI.html Via Dartmouth.edu]</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Augustan, Volumes 17-20 |date=1975 |publisher=Augustan Society |page=34 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Oh9ZAAAAMAAJ&q=They+reveal+the+real+origin+of+the+Aisin+Gioro+family&dq=They+reveal+the+real+origin+of+the+Aisin+Gioro+family}}</ref> In the Ming period, the Koreans of [[Joseon]] referred to the Jurchen inhabited lands north of the Korean peninsula, above the rivers Yalu and Tumen to be part of Ming China, as the \"superior country\" (sangguk) which they called Ming China.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kim |first1=Sun Joo |title=The Northern Region of Korea: History, Identity, and Culture |date=2011 |publisher=University of Washington Press |isbn=978-0295802176 |page=19 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KcYthUKyeS0C&pg=PA19}}</ref> The Qing deliberately excluded references and information that showed the Jurchens (Manchus) as subservient to the Ming dynasty, from the [[History of Ming]] to hide their former subservient relationship to the Ming. The ''[[Veritable Records of the Ming]]'' were not used to source content on Jurchens during Ming rule in the History of Ming because of this.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Richard J. |title=The Qing Dynasty and Traditional Chinese Culture |date=2015 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1442221949 |page=216 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RhmaCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA216}}</ref> This historical revisionism helped remove the accusation of rebellion from the Qing ruling family refusing to mention in the Mingshi the fact that the Qing founders were Ming China's subjects.<ref>{{cite book |page=219 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MrYfAQAAMAAJ&q=The+Mingshi+scrupulously+avoids+any+mention+of+the+fact+that+the+founders+of+the+Qingdynasty+were+at+one+time+subjects+of+Ming+China,+thus+sparing+the+Qing+ruling+house+the+charge+of+rebellion.&dq=The+Mingshi+scrupulously+avoids+any+mention+of+the+fact+that+the+founders+of+the+Qingdynasty+were+at+one+time+subjects+of+Ming+China,+thus+sparing+the+Qing+ruling+house+the+charge+of+rebellion. |last=Fryslie |first=Matthew |title=The historian's castrated slave: the textual eunuch and the creation of historical identity in the Ming history |date=2001 |publisher=University of Michigan }}</ref> The Qing [[Yongzheng Emperor]] attempted to rewrite the historical record and claim that the Aisin Gioro were never subjects of past dynasties and empires trying to cast [[Nurhaci]]'s acceptance of Ming titles like Dragon Tiger General (longhu jiangjun \u9f8d\u864e\u5c07\u8ecd) by claiming he accepted to \"please Heaven\".<ref>{{cite book |pages=303\u20134  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hbEwDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA303#v=onepage&q&f=false |last=Crossley |first=Pamela Kyle |title=A Translucent Mirror: History and Identity in Qing Imperial Ideology |date=2002 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=0520234243 |edition=illustrated, reprint}}</ref>\n\n==Intermarriage and political alliances==\nThe Qing emperors arranged marriages between Aisin Gioro noblewomen and outsiders to create political marriage alliances. During the [[Qing conquest of the Ming|Manchu conquest]] of the [[Ming dynasty|Ming Empire]], the Manchu rulers offered to marry their princesses to [[Han Chinese]] military officers who served the Ming Empire as a means of inducing these officers into surrendering or defecting to their side. Aisin Gioro princesses were also married to Mongol princes, for the purpose of forming alliances between the Manchus and Mongol tribes.<ref>{{cite book|year=2008|publisher=University of California Press|volume=Volume 7 of The California world history library |quote=Whereas the emperor and princes chose wives or concubines from the banner population through the drafts, imperial daughters were married to Mongol princes, Manchu aristocrats, or, on some occasions, Chinese high officials... To win the support and cooperation of Ming generals in Liaodong, Nurhaci gave them Aisin Gioro women as wives. In 1618, before he attacked Fushun city, he promised the Ming general defending the city a woman from the Aisin Gioro clan in marriage if he surrendered. After the general surrendered, Nurhaci gave him one of his granddaughters. Later the general joined the Chinese banner.|location=|page=148|title=Servants of the dynasty: palace women in world history|edition=illustrated|editor=Anne Walthall |jstor=10.1525/j.ctt1ppzvr|isbn=9780520254435}}</ref>\n\nThe Manchus successfully induced one Han Chinese general, [[Li Yongfang]] (\u674e\u6c38\u82b3), into defecting to their side by offering him a position in the Manchu banners. Li Yongfang also married the daughter of [[Abatai]], a son of the Qing dynasty's founder [[Nurhaci]]. Many more Han Chinese abandoned their posts in the Ming Empire and defected to the Manchu side.<ref>{{cite book|year=1977|publisher=Simon and Schuster|quote=Chinese elements had joined the Manchu armies as early as 1618 when the Ming commander Li Yung-fang surrendered at Fu-shun. Li was made a banner general, was given gifts of slaves and serfs, and was betrothed to a young woman of the Aisin Gioro clan. Although Li's surrender at the time was exceptional, his integration into the Manchu elite was only the first of many such defections by border generals and their subordinates, who shaved their heads and accepted Manchu customs. It was upon these prisoners, then, that Abahai relied to form new military units to fight their former master, the Ming Emperor.|location=|isbn=978-0-02-933680-9|page=79|title=The fall of imperial China|edition=illustrated, reprint |author=Frederic E. Wakeman, Jr.}}</ref> There were over 1,000 marriages between Han Chinese men and Manchu women in 1632 \u2013 due to a proposal by [[Yoto (prince)|Yoto]] (\u5cb3\u6258), a nephew of the Manchu emperor [[Hong Taiji]].<ref>{{cite book|year=2008|publisher=University of California Press|volume=Volume 7 of The California world history library |quote=In 1632, Hongtaiji accepted the suggestion of Prince Yoto, his nephew, and assigned one thousand Manchu women to surrendered Chinese officials and generals for them to marry. He also classified these Chinese into groups by rank and gave them wives accordingly. \"First-rank officials were given Manchu princes' daughters as wives; second rank officials were given Manchu ministers' daughters as wives.\"|location=|isbn=<!--0-520-25444-9-->|page=148|title=Servants of the dynasty: palace women in world history|edition=illustrated|editor=Anne Walthall |jstor=10.1525/j.ctt1ppzvr}}</ref> Hong Taiji believed that intermarriage between Han Chinese and Manchus could help to eliminate ethnic conflicts in areas already occupied by the Manchus, as well as help the Han Chinese forget their ancestral roots more easily.<ref>{{cite book|year=2008|publisher=University of California Press|volume=Volume 7 of The California world history library |quote=Hongtaiji believed that only through intermarrige between Chinese and Manchus would he be able to eliminate ethnic conflicts in the areas he conquered; and \"since the Chinese generals and Manchu women lived together and ate together, it would help these surrendered generals to forget their motherland\"|location= |isbn=<!--0-520-25444-9-->|page=148|title=Servants of the dynasty: palace women in world history|edition=illustrated|editor=Anne Walthall |jstor=10.1525/j.ctt1ppzvr}}</ref>\n\nManchu noblewomen were also married to Han Chinese men who surrendered or defected to the Manchu side.<ref>{{cite book|year=2008|publisher=University of California Press|volume=Volume 7 of The California world history library |quote=During their first years in China, the Manchu rulers continued to give imperial daughters to Chinese high officials. These included the sons of the Three Feudatories\u2014the Ming defectors rewarded with large and almost autonomous fiefs in the south.|location= |isbn=<!--0-520-25444-9-->|page=148|title=Servants of the dynasty: palace women in world history|edition=illustrated|editor=Anne Walthall |jstor=10.1525/j.ctt1ppzvr}}</ref> Aisin Gioro women were married to the sons of the Han Chinese generals [[Sun Sike]] (\u5b6b\u601d\u514b), [[Geng Jimao]], [[Shang Kexi]] and [[Wu Sangui]].<ref name=\"Watson1991\"/> The [[Royal and noble ranks of the Qing dynasty#Princesses' consorts|''e'fu'']] (\u984d\u99d9) rank was given to husbands of Manchu princesses. Geng Zhongming, a Han bannerman, was awarded the title \"Prince Jingnan\", while his grandsons Geng Jingzhong, Geng Zhaozhong (\u803f\u662d\u5fe0) and Geng Juzhong (\u803f\u805a\u5fe0) married [[Hooge, Prince Su|Hooge]]'s daughter, [[Abatai]]'s granddaughter, and [[Yolo (prince)|Yolo]]'s daughter respectively.<ref>{{cite book |author=Frederic E. Wakeman, Jr. |title=The Great Enterprise: The Manchu Reconstruction of Imperial Order in Seventeenth-century China|year=1985|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-04804-1 |pages=1017\u2013}}</ref> Sun Sike's son, Sun Cheng'en (\u5b6b\u627f\u6069), married the [[Kangxi Emperor]]'s fourth daughter, Heshuo Princess Quejing (\u548c\u7855\u60ab\u9756\u516c\u4e3b).<ref name=\"Watson1991\">{{cite book |editor1=Rubie Sharon Watson|editor2=Patricia Buckley Ebrey|title=Marriage and Inequality in Chinese Society|year=1991|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-07124-7|pages=179\u2013}}</ref>\n\nImperial Duke Who Assists the State (\u5b97\u5ba4\u8f14\u570b\u516c) Aisin Gioro Suyan's (\u8607\u71d5) daughter was married to Han Chinese Banner General [[Nian Gengyao]].<ref name=\"\u5510\u535a2010\">{{cite book|author=\u5510\u535a|title=\u6e05\u671d\u6b0a\u81e3\u56de\u61b6\u9304|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JSi4AAAAQBAJ&pg=PA108&dq=%E8%BC%94%E5%9C%8B%E5%85%AC%E8%98%87%E7%87%95#v=onepage&q=%E8%BC%94%E5%9C%8B%E5%85%AC%E8%98%87%E7%87%95&f=false|year=2010|publisher=\u9060\u6d41\u51fa\u7248|isbn=978-957-32-6691-4|pages=108\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"\u65bd\u6a39\u797f2012\">{{cite book|author=\u65bd\u6a39\u797f|title=\u4e16\u754c\u6b77\u53f2\u6230\u4e8b\u50b3\u5947|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ODdaBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA198&dq=%E8%BC%94%E5%9C%8B%E5%85%AC%E8%98%87%E7%87%95#v=onepage&q=%E8%BC%94%E5%9C%8B%E5%85%AC%E8%98%87%E7%87%95&f=false|date=17 May 2012|publisher=\u83ef\u5fd7\u6587\u5316|isbn=978-986-5936-00-6|pages=198\u2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=2016-03-07|title=\u6e05\u4ee3\u7b2c\u4e00\u6218\u795e\u662f\u8c01? \u5e74\u7fb9\u5c27\u548c\u5cb3\u949f\u742a\u8c01\u7684\u6210\u5c31\u66f4\u9ad8?|url=http://www.lishi.com/news/201603/7645.html|newspaper=\u5386\u53f2\u7f51|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828192434/http://www.lishi.com/news/201603/7645.html|archivedate=2016-08-28}}</ref>\n\n==Genetics==\n[[Haplogroup C-M217|Haplogroup C3b2b1*-M401(xF5483)]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wei |first1=Ryan Lan-Hai |last2=Yan |first2=Shi |last3=Yu |first3=Ge |last4=Huang |first4=Yun-Zhi |title=Genetic trail for the early migrations of Aisin Gioro, the imperial house of the Qing dynasty |journal=Journal of Human Genetics |date=November 2016 |volume=62 |issue=3 |pages=407\u2013411 |doi=10.1038/jhg.2016.142|pmid=27853133 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Yan |first1=Shi |last2=Tachibana |first2=Harumasa |last3=Wei |first3=Lan-Hai |last4=Yu |first4=Ge |last5=Wen |first5=Shao-Qing |last6=Wang |first6=Chuan-Chao |title=Y chromosome of Aisin Gioro, the imperial house of the Qing dynasty. |journal=Journal of Human Genetics |date=June 2015 |volume=60 |issue=6 |pages=295\u20138 |doi=10.1038/jhg.2015.28 |pmid=25833470 |arxiv=1412.6274 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Did you know DNA was used to uncover the origin of the House of Aisin Gioro? |url=https://www.didyouknowdna.com/famous-dna/aisin-gioro-dna/ |website=Did You Know DNA...}}</ref> has been identified as a possible marker of the Aisin Gioro and is found in ten different ethnic minorities in northern China, but completely absent from Han Chinese.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.cell.com/ajhg/pdf/S0002-9297(07)63394-1.pdf |title=Recent Spread of a Y-Chromosomal Lineage in Northern China and Mongolia  |accessdate=2015-11-26 |doi=10.1086/498583 |volume=77 |issue=6  |journal=The American Journal of Human Genetics |pages=1112\u20131116 |pmid=16380921 |pmc=1285168 |year=2005 | last1 = Xue | first1 = Yali | last2 = Zerjal | first2 = Tatiana | last3 = Bao | first3 = Weidong | last4 = Zhu | first4 = Suling | last5 = Lim | first5 = Si-Keun | last6 = Shu | first6 = Qunfang | last7 = Xu | first7 = Jiujin | last8 = Du | first8 = Ruofu | last9 = Fu | first9 = Songbin | last10 = Li | first10 = Pu | last11 = Yang | first11 = Huanming | last12 = Tyler-Smith | first12 = Chris }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.genebase.com/learning/article/23 |title=Asian Ancestry based on Studies of Y-DNA Variation: Part 3. Recent demographics and ancestry of the male East Asians \u2013 Empires and Dynasties |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131125053101/http://www.genebase.com/learning/article/23 |archive-date=November 25, 2013 |work=Genebase Tutorials }}</ref>\n\n==Notable Aisin Gioros==\n===Emperors===\n{{Main|List of emperors of the Qing dynasty}}\n{{see also|Chinese emperors family tree (late)#Qing dynasty|l1=Aisin Gioro family tree}}\n\n* [[Nurhaci]] (1559\u20131626), founder of the Qing dynasty\n* [[Hong Taiji]] (1592\u20131643), Nurhaci's eighth son\n* Fulin (1638\u20131661), the [[Shunzhi Emperor]], Hong Taiji's ninth son\n* Xuanye (1654\u20131722), the [[Kangxi Emperor]], the Shunzhi Emperor's third son\n* Yinzhen (1678\u20131735), the [[Yongzheng Emperor]], the Kangxi Emperor's fourth son\n* Hongli (1711\u20131799), the [[Qianlong Emperor]], the Yongzheng Emperor's fourth son\n* Yongyan (1760\u20131820), the [[Jiaqing Emperor]], the Qianlong Emperor's 15th son\n* Minning (1782\u20131850), the [[Daoguang Emperor]], the Jiaqing Emperor's second son\n* Yizhu (1831\u20131861), the [[Xianfeng Emperor]], the Daoguang Emperor's fourth son\n* Zaichun (1856\u20131875), the [[Tongzhi Emperor]], the Xianfeng Emperor's first son\n* Zaitian (1871\u20131908), the [[Guangxu Emperor]], [[Yixuan, Prince Chun|Yixuan]]'s second son, symbolically adopted as the Xianfeng Emperor's son\n* [[Puyi]] (1906\u20131967), the Xuantong Emperor, [[Zaifeng, Prince Chun|Zaifeng]]'s first son, symbolically adopted as the Tongzhi Emperor's son\n\n===Iron-cap princes and their descendants===\n{{Main|Royal and noble ranks of the Qing dynasty#Male members}}\n\nAccording to Qing dynasty imperial tradition, the sons of princes do not automatically inherit their fathers' titles in the same rank as their fathers. For example, [[Yongqi, Prince Rong|Yongqi]] held the title \"[[Prince Rong|Prince Rong of the First Rank]]\", but when his title was passed on to his son, Mianyi, it became \"Prince Rong of the Second Rank\". In other words, the title gets diminished by one rank as it is passed down to each subsequent generation, but generally to no lower than the rank of [[Royal and noble ranks of the Qing dynasty#Male members|''kesi-be tuwakiyara gurun-de aisilara gung'']] (second class imperial duke). However, there were 12 princes who were awarded the [[Royal and noble ranks of the Qing dynasty#Rule of inheritance|''shi xi wang ti'' (perpetual heritability, a.k.a. \"iron-cap\")]] privilege, which meant that their titles can be passed on to subsequent generations without the downgrading effect.\n\nThe 12 \"iron-cap\" princely peerages are listed as follows. Some of them were renamed at different points in time, hence they had multiple names.\n\n* [[Prince Zheng|Prince Zheng / Prince Jian]], the line of [[Jirgalang]] (1599\u20131655), descendant of [[Taksi]]\n* [[Prince Li (\u79ae)|Prince Li / Prince Xun / Prince Kang]], the line of [[Dai\u0161an]] (1583\u20131648), descendant of [[Nurhaci]]\n** [[Prince Keqin|Prince Keqin / Prince Cheng / Prince Ping / Prince Yanxi]], the line of [[Yoto (prince)|Yoto]] (1599\u20131639), descendant of [[Nurhaci]]\n*** [[Prince Shuncheng]], the line of [[Lekdehun]] (1619\u20131652), descendant of [[Nurhaci]]\n* [[Prince Rui (\u777f)|Prince Rui]], the line of [[Dorgon]] (1612\u20131650), descendant of [[Nurhaci]]\n* [[Prince Yu (\u8c6b)|Prince Yu]], the line of [[Dodo, Prince Yu|Dodo]] (1614\u20131649), descendant of [[Nurhaci]]\n* [[Prince Su|Prince Su / Prince Xian]], the line of [[Hooge, Prince Su|Hooge]] (1609\u20131648), descendant of [[Hong Taiji]]\n* [[Prince Zhuang|Prince Chengze / Prince Zhuang]], the line of [[\u0160ose]] (1629\u20131655), descendant of [[Hong Taiji]]\n* [[Prince Yi (\u6021)|Prince Yi]], the line of [[Yinxiang (prince)|Yinxiang]] (1686\u20131730), descendant of [[Kangxi Emperor]]\n* [[Prince Qing]], the line of [[Yonglin]] (1766\u20131820), descendant of [[Qianlong Emperor]]\n* [[Prince Gong (peerage)|Prince Gong]], the line of [[Prince Gong|Yixin]] (1833\u20131898), descendant of [[Daoguang Emperor]]\n* [[Prince Chun (\u9187)|Prince Chun]], the line of [[Yixuan, Prince Chun|Yixuan]] (1840\u20131891), descendant of [[Daoguang Emperor]]\n\n===Prominent political figures===\n* [[Dai\u0161an]] (1583-1648), Nurhaci's second son, participated in the [[Qing conquest of the Ming]]\n* [[Jirgalang]] (1599\u20131655), Nurhaci's nephew, co-regent with Dorgon during the Shunzhi Emperor's early reign\n* [[Ajige]] (1605\u20131651), Nurhaci's 12th son, participated in the Qing conquest of the Ming\n* [[Dorgon]] (1612\u20131650), Nurhaci's 14th son, [[Prince regent|Prince-Regent]] and ''de facto'' ruler during the Shunzhi Emperor's early reign\n* [[Dodo, Prince Yu|Dodo]] (1614\u20131649), Nurhaci's 15th son, participated in the Qing conquest of the Ming\n* [[Yunsi|Yinsi]] (1681\u20131726), the Kangxi Emperor's eighth son, Yinzhen's competitor for the succession, expelled from the Aisin Gioro clan later\n* [[Yinxiang (prince)|Yinxiang]] (1686\u20131730), the Kangxi Emperor's 13th son, Yinzhen's ally\n* [[Yunti, Prince Xun|Yinti]] (1688\u20131756), the Kangxi Emperor's 14th son, Yinzhen's competitor for the succession, purported rightful heir to the throne\n* [[Duanhua]] (1807\u20131861), descendant of [[Jirgalang]], regent for the Tongzhi Emperor, ousted from power in the [[Xinyou Coup]] in 1861\n* [[Sushun (Qing dynasty)|Sushun]] (1816\u20131861), Duanhua's brother, regent for the Tongzhi Emperor, ousted from power in the Xinyou Coup in 1861\n* [[Zaiyuan]] (1816\u20131861), descendant of Yinxiang, regent for the Tongzhi Emperor, ousted from power in the Xinyou Coup in 1861\n* [[Prince Gong|Yixin]] (1833\u20131898), the Daoguang Emperor's sixth son, Prince-Regent during the Tongzhi Emperor's reign\n* [[Yikuang]] (1838\u20131917), descendant of [[Yonglin]], Prime Minister of the Imperial Cabinet\n* [[Yixuan, Prince Chun|Yixuan]] (1840\u20131891), the Daoguang Emperor's seventh son, the Guangxu Emperor's biological father\n* [[Zaiyi]] (1856\u20131922), [[Yicong]]'s son, [[Boxer Rebellion]] leader\n* [[Zaize]] (1876\u20131929), a sixth-generation descendant of the Kangxi Emperor, Finance Minister and Salt Policy Minister in the Imperial Cabinet\n* [[Zaizhen]] (1876\u20131947), Yikuang's son, court minister\n* [[Zaifeng, Prince Chun|Zaifeng]] (1883\u20131951), Yixuan's son, Puyi's biological father, Prince-Regent during Puyi's reign\n* [[Zaixun, Prince Rui|Zaixun]] (1885\u20131949), Yixuan's sixth son, Navy Minister in the Imperial Cabinet\n\n===20th century \u2013 present===\n* Pujin (\u6ea5\u4f12; 1893\u20131966), better known as [[Pu Xuezhai]] (\u6ea5\u96ea\u9f4b), [[guqin]] player and [[Chinese painting]] artist, grandson of [[Yicong|Yicong (Prince Dun)]]\n* [[Puru (artist)|Puru]] (1896\u20131963), Taiwanese artist and calligrapher, grandson of [[Prince Gong|Yixin (Prince Gong)]]\n* [[Jin Guangping]] (1899\u20131966), born Aisin Gioro Hengxu, scholar of the [[Jurchen language|Jurchen]] and [[Khitan language|Khitan]] languages\n* [[Yoshiko Kawashima]] (1907\u20131948), born Aisin Gioro Xianyu, a spy for the [[Japanese Empire]] during the [[Second Sino-Japanese War|Sino-Japanese War]]\n* [[Pujie]] (1907\u20131994), [[Puyi]]'s brother, member of the [[Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]], nominal head of the Aisin Gioro clan from 1967\u20131994\n* [[Qigong (artist)|Qigong]] (1912\u20132005), artist and calligrapher, descended from the [[Prince He|Prince He peerage]]\n* [[Yuyan]] (1918\u20131997), calligrapher, distant nephew of [[Puyi]]\n* [[Jin Qicong]] (1918\u20132004), Jin Guangping's son, historian and scholar of the Jurchen and [[Manchu language|Manchu]] languages\n* [[Jin Moyu]] (1918\u20132014), born Aisin Gioro Xianqi, [[Yoshiko Kawashima]]'s younger sister, educator\n* [[Jin Youzhi]] (1918\u20132015), born Aisin Gioro Puren, [[Puyi]]'s half-brother, nominal head of the Aisin Gioro clan from 1994\u20132015\n* [[Aisin Gioro Yuhuan]] (1929\u20132003), [[sanxian]] player and [[Chinese painting]] artist\n* [[Jin Yuzhang]] (born 1942), Jin Youzhi's son, governor of Beijing's [[Chongwen District]], nominal head of the Aisin Gioro clan since 2015\n* [[King Pu-tsung|Jin Pucong]] (born 1956), Taiwanese politician, allegedly<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.libertytimes.com.tw/2009/new/dec/14/today-o6.htm |script-title=zh:\u91d1\u6ea5\u8070\u662f\u4e0d\u662f\u6ea5\u5100\u7684\u5802\u5f1f\uff1f |trans-title=King Pu-tsung is not the cousin of Henry Puyi? |author=\u66f9\u9577\u9752 |publisher=[[Liberty Times]] |location=Taiwan |date=2009-12-14 |language=zh |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091217031448/http://www.libertytimes.com.tw/2009/new/dec/14/today-o6.htm |archivedate=2009-12-17 |author-link=:zh:\u66f9\u9577\u9752 }}</ref> descended from the Aisin Gioro clan\n* [[Aisin-Gioro Ulhicun]] (born 1958), Jin Qicong's daughter, historian and scholar of the Jurchen, Khitan and Manchu languages\n* [[Zhao Junzhe]] (born 1979), football player, descended from [[Boolungga]], the fifth brother of [[Nurhaci]]'s grandfather [[Giocangga]]\n* [[Ariel Aisin-Gioro]] (born 1983), actress\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery caption=\" Images \" heights=165 mode=packed>\nFile:\u6069\u683c\u5fb7\u5c14\u6765\u4e0a\u5c0a\u53f7\u56fe.jpg|[[Nurhaci]] on his throne\nFile:\u6e05 \u4f5a\u540d \u300a\u6e05\u592a\u7956\u5929\u547d\u7687\u5e1d\u671d\u670d\u50cf\u300b.jpg|Nurhaci\nFile:Nurhaci image.JPG|Nurhaci\nFile:Nurhaci.jpg|Nurhaci\nFile:Qing-Nurhaci.jpg|Nurhaci\nFile:HenryPuYi.jpeg|[[Puyi|Prince Puyi]]\nFile:Prince Zaitao of Qing.jpg|[[Zaitao]]\nFile:Prince Zaitao in the United States